{"title_page": "Blue toe syndrome", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = <!--{{PAGENAME}} by default-->\n| synonym         = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| pronounce       = \n| specialty       = <!-- from Wikidata, can be overwritten -->\n| symptoms        =\n| complications   =\n| onset           =\n| duration        =\n| types           = \n| causes          =\n| risks           =\n| diagnosis       =\n| differential    =\n| prevention      =\n| treatment       =\n| medication      =\n| prognosis       =\n| frequency       =\n| deaths          =\n}}\n'''Blue toe syndrome''' is a situation that may reflect atherothrombotic [[microembolism]], causing transient focal ischaemia, occasionally with minor apparent tissue loss, but without diffuse forefoot [[ischemia]].<ref>[http://download.journals.elsevierhealth.com/pdfs/journals/0741-5214/PIIS0741521497700454.pdf 'Standards for vascular reporting']</ref> The development of blue or violaceous toes can also occur with trauma, cold-induced injury, disorders producing generalized cyanosis, decreased arterial flow, impaired venous outflow, and abnormal circulating blood.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 10834489 | volume=11 | issue=5 | title=Blue toe syndrome: treatment with intra-arterial stents and review of therapies | year=2000 | journal=J Vasc Interv Radiol | pages=585\u201392 | vauthors=Matchett WJ, McFarland DR, Eidt JF, Moursi MM }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 8889381 | volume=11 | issue=5 | title=Evaluation and management of cholesterol embolization and the blue toe syndrome | year=1996 | journal=Curr Opin Cardiol | pages=533\u201342 | vauthors=Applebaum RM, Kronzon I }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 9047906 | issue=14 | title=[Cholesterol (cholestelin) embolization syndrome--blue toe syndrome] | year=1996 | journal=Ryoikibetsu Shokogun Shirizu | pages=469\u201372 | vauthors=Ishihara T, Ohkubo T, Nakano T, Ohsawa N }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 8746834 | doi=10.1007/BF02018830 | volume=9 | issue=6 | title=Blue toe syndrome from a \"coral reef\" aorta | year=1995 | journal=Ann Vasc Surg | pages=561\u20134 | vauthors=Rosenberg GD, Killewich LA }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 7963875 | volume=13 | issue=2 | title=Femoral artery hypoplasia and persistent sciatic artery with blue toe syndrome: a case report, histologic analysis and review of the literature | year=1994 | journal=Int Angiol | pages=154\u20139 | vauthors=Sottiurai VS, Omlie W }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 1444678 | volume=152 | issue=11 | title=Blue toe syndrome. Causes and management | year=1992 | journal=Arch Intern Med | pages=2197\u2013202 | vauthors=O'Keeffe ST, Woods BO, Breslin DJ, Tsapatsaris NP }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 27274647 | doi=10.5021/ad.2016.28.3.400 | volume=28 | issue=3 | title=Blue Toe Syndrome as an Early Sign of Disseminated Intravascular Coagulation | pmc=4884725 | year=2016 | journal=Ann Dermatol | pages=400\u20131 | vauthors=Choi KH, Yoo J, Huh JW, Jeong YI, Kim MS, Jue MS, Park HJ }}</ref><ref>\n{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.jaad.2008.09.038 | pmid=19103358 | volume=60 | title=Blue (or purple) toe syndrome | date=January 2009 | journal=J. Am. Acad. Dermatol. | pages=1\u201320; quiz 21\u20132 | vauthors=Hirschmann JV, Raugi GJ }}\n</ref>\nThe terms \"blue toe syndrome\", \"grey toe syndrome\" and \"purple toe syndrome\" are sometimes used interchangeably.<ref name=\"pmid19103358\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Hirschmann JV, Raugi GJ |title=Blue (or purple) toe syndrome |journal=J. Am. Acad. Dermatol. |volume=60 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201320; quiz 21\u20132 |date=January 2009 |pmid=19103358 |doi=10.1016/j.jaad.2008.09.038 }}</ref>\n\nStudies may include [[echocardiography]], thoracic and abdominal CT or MRI,<ref>Blackshear JL, Oldenburg WA, Cohen MD. \"Making the diagnosis when the patient has 'blue toes'.\" ''Geriatrics'' 1994 Dec;49(12):37-9, 43-5.\n</ref><ref>Kopani K, Liao S, Shaffer K. \"The Coral Reef Aorta: Diagnosis and Treatment Following CT.\" Radiol Case Rep. 2009; 4(1):209. Epub 2016 Oct 4.</ref><ref>Belczak SQ, Sincos IR, Aun R, Costa KV, Araujo EA. \"Coral reef aorta, emergency surgical: case report and literature review.\" ''Einstein (Sao Paulo)'' 2014 Apr; 12(2):237-41.</ref><ref>Schulte KM, Reiher L, Grabitz L, Sandmann W.  \"Coral reef aorta: a long-term study of 21 patients.\n''Ann Vasc Surg.'' 2000 Nov; 14(6):626-33.</ref><ref>The Coral Reef Aorta: Diagnosis and Treatment Following CT.\n''Radiol Case Rep.'' 2016 Oct 4;4(1):209.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 23518854 | doi=10.1177/1708538113478764 | volume=21 | issue=4 | title=Coral reef aorta: case report and review of the literature | year=2013 | journal=Vascular | pages=251\u20139 | vauthors=Policha A, Moudgill N, Eisenberg J, Rao A, DiMuzio P }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 6492313 | volume=1 | issue=6 | title=\"Coral reef\" atherosclerosis of the suprarenal aorta: a unique clinical entity | year=1984 | journal=J Vasc Surg | pages=903\u20139 | vauthors=Qvarfordt PG, Reilly LM, Sedwitz MM, Ehrenfeld WK, Stoney RJ }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 22477301 | volume=16 | issue=3 | title=The coral reef aorta - a single centre experience in 70 patients | pmc=2733021 | year=2007 | journal=Int J Angiol | pages=98\u2013105 | vauthors=Grotemeyer D, Pourhassan S, Rehbein H, Voiculescu A, Reinecke P, Sandmann W }}</ref> peripheral arterial run off imaging studies,<ref>Blackshear JL, Oldenburg WA, Cohen MD.  \"Making the diagnosis when the patient has 'blue toes'. ''Geriatrics'' 1994 Dec;49(12):37-9, 43-5.</ref> hypercoagulopathy labs,<ref>Blackshear JL, Oldenburg WA, Cohen MD. \"Making the diagnosis when the patient has 'blue toes'.\" ''Geriatrics'' 1994 Dec;49(12):37-9, 43-5.\n</ref> and interrogation of syndromes that lead to peripheral vascular pathology.<ref>Blackshear JL, Oldenburg WA, Cohen MD. \"Making the diagnosis when the patient has 'blue toes'.\" ''Geriatrics'' 1994 Dec;49(12):37-9, 43-5.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Warfarin#Purple toe syndrome]]\n* [[Cholesterol embolism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Pictures are available on this link. [http://www.medscape.com/content/2000/00/40/90/409090/art-ahj1392.07.fig1.jpg 'Blue toe syndrome']\n* {{cite journal | pmid = 17624153 | volume=151 | issue=23 | title=[Blue toe syndrome; a sign of end-arterial occlusion] | year=2007 | journal=Ned Tijdschr Geneeskd | pages=1261\u20137 |vauthors=Nijhof IS, Majoie IM, Dijkhorst-Oei LT, Bousema MT }}\n\n[[Category:Foot diseases]]\n[[Category:Ischemia]]\n[[Category:Syndromes affecting the cardiovascular system]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = <!--{{PAGENAME}} by default-->\n| synonym         = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| pronounce       = \n| specialty       = <!-- from Wikidata, can be overwritten -->\n| symptoms        =\n| complications   =\n| onset           =\n| duration        =\n| types           = \n| causes          =\n| risks           =\n| diagnosis       =\n| differential    =\n| prevention      =\n| treatment       =\n| medication      =\n| prognosis       =\n| frequency       =\n| deaths          =\n}}\n'''Blue toe syndrome''' is a situation that may reflect atherothrombotic [[microembolism]], causing transient focal ischaemia, occasionally with minor apparent tissue loss, but without diffuse forefoot [[ischemia]].<ref>[http://download.journals.elsevierhealth.com/pdfs/journals/0741-5214/PIIS0741521497700454.pdf 'Standards for vascular reporting']</ref> The development of blue or violaceous toes can also occur with trauma, cold-induced injury, disorders producing generalized cyanosis, decreased arterial flow, impaired venous outflow, and abnormal circulating blood.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 10834489 | volume=11 | issue=5 | title=Blue toe syndrome: treatment with intra-arterial stents a