{"title_page": "Sailing yacht", "text_new": "{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 400\n\n | image1 = 2013_Ahmanson_Cup_Regatta_yacht_Zapata_II_b_photo_D_Ramey_Logan.jpg\n | alt1 = A cruising yacht\n | caption1 = A {{Convert|50|ft|m|abbr=|adj=on}} cruising yacht\n\n | image2 = 60feet IMOCA SAFRAN 01.JPG\n | alt2 = A racing yacht\n | caption2 = A {{Convert|60|ft|m|abbr=|adj=on}} [[IMOCA 60|IMOCA]] ocean racing yacht\n\n | footer = Cruising and racing yachts embody different tradeoffs between comfort and performance.\n}}\n\nA '''sailing yacht''' (US ship prefixes SY or S/Y), is a leisure craft that uses sails as its primary means of propulsion. A yacht may be a sail or power vessel used for pleasure, cruising, or racing.<ref name=\"Webster\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/yacht|title=Definition of YACHT|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/us/dictionary/english/yacht|title=YACHT {{!}} definition in the Cambridge English Dictionary|website=dictionary.cambridge.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/us/dictionary/english/yacht|title=Yacht definition and meaning {{!}} Collins English Dictionary|website=www.collinsdictionary.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> There is no standard definition, so the term applies here to sailing vessels that have a cabin with amenities that accommodate overnight use. To be termed a \"yacht\", as opposed to a \"boat\", such a vessel is likely to be at least {{Convert|33|ft|m|abbr=}} in length and have been judged to have good aesthetic qualities.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boats.com/on-the-water/when-is-a-boat-also-a-yacht/|title=When is a Boat Also a Yacht? - boats.com|last=Kavin|first=Kim|date=June 4, 2018|website=www.boats.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> [[Sailboat|Sailboats]] that don't accommodate overnight use or are smaller than {{Convert|30|ft|m|abbr=}} are not universally called yachts. Sailing yachts in excess of {{Convert|40|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip}} are generally considered to be [[Superyacht|superyachts]].<ref name=\"Perry\">{{Cite book|last=Perry, Julie|title=Insiders' guide to becoming a yacht stewardess : confessions from my years afloat with the rich and famous|date=August 2013|isbn=978-1-61448-786-9|edition=Second|location=New York|oclc=859781233}}</ref>\n\nSailing [[yacht]]s are actively used in sport and are among categories recognized by the governing body of sailing sports, [[World Sailing]].<ref>[http://www.sailing.org/classes/#isaf_sliding_tab_item_classes_index_yacht World Sailing classes of yachts].</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe history of pleasure boats begins with rowed craft in Pharaonic Egyptian times. The history of sailing yachts begins in Europe in the beginning of the 1600s with the building of a pleasure vessel for the son of [[James VI and I|King James I of England]]. Pleasure vessels acquired the name ''yacht'' after the time of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], who spent time exiled in Europe and visited the Netherlands, where a variety of yachts (''jaghts'' in Dutch) were already well-developed as pleasure boats for the elite classes since the beginning of the 17th century. Upon his restoration to the English crown, Charles commissioned a series of royal yachts, which included at least one experimental [[catamaran]]. The first recorded yacht race between two vessels occurred in 1661, followed by the first open sailing competition in 1663 in English waters.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Herreshoff|first=L. Francis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q4RONp_1mrMC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=history+of+sailing+yachts&hl=en|title=The Golden Age of Yachting|date=2007|publisher=Sheridan House, Inc.|year=|isbn=978-1-57409-251-6|location=|pages=19-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 1739, England found itself in a series of wars\u2014a period that saw a decline in yachting. In Ireland, however, the gentry enjoyed yachting and founded the first yacht club in Cork as the Cork Harbor Water Club in 1720. English yacht racing continued among the English gentry who founded England's oldest yacht club in 1775 to support a fleet at [[Cumberland]]. With maritime peace, starting in 1815, came a resurgence of interest in yachting. Boatbuilders, who had been making fast vessels both for smugglers and the government [[Cutter (boat)|revenue cutters]], turned their skills again to yachts.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Evolution of design ===\nThe fast yachts of the early 19th century were typically [[lugger]]s, [[schooner]]s, or [[sloop]]s with [[fore-and-aft rig]]s. By the 1850s, yachts featured large sail areas, a narrow beam, and a deeper draft than was customary until then. Racing between yachts owned by wealthy patrons was common, with large wagers at stake. The [[America's Cup]] arose out of a contest between the yacht, ''[[America (yacht)|America]]'', and its English competitors. Both countries had rules by which to rate yachts, the English by tonnage and the American by length.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nEnglish and American design philosophies for sailing yachts diverged in the early 1800s: the English favoring a narrow [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] (width) and a deep-draft keel and the Americans favoring a broad beam and a shallow draft with a moveable centerboard to provide lateral resistance and righting moment. In 1851, when the yacht ''America'' crossed to England, the two design philosophies were converging back towards each other. ''America's'' pointed, convex bow and maximum beam, placed aft, influenced British designs, thanks to her racing successes against the British competition. American yachtsmen, in turn, found that their shallow \"skimming-dish\" designs weren't faster or safer than the visiting English yachts.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Doane, Charles J.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/551161085|title=The modern cruising sailboat : a complete guide to its design, construction, and outfitting|date=2010|publisher=International Marine|isbn=978-0-07-163700-8|location=Camden, Me.|oclc=551161085}}</ref>\n\nBy the turn of the 20th century, racing yachts featured long overhangs, fore and aft, and a narrow, deep keel by historic standards. Along the way, yacht designers discovered that handicapping rules based on tonnage or length were not good indicators of performance, although they remained a basis for taxation in the two home countries.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Cruising yachts ===\nThe prevalent purpose of yachting under sail in the 19th was racing. Boats would cross the Atlantic to engage the yachts of other owners in contests of speed. Cruising was the provenance of the most wealthy in large, luxurious yachts that had reliable auxiliary power or were solely steam-powered yachts.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEarly explorers in smaller sailing craft wrote of their experiences cruising the lakes and canals of Europe in a sailing canoe ([[John MacGregor (sportsman)|John MacGregor]]) and the near-shore waters of England and Scotland in a {{Convert|20|ft|m|abbr=|adj=on}} [[Cutter (boat)|cutter]] (R.T. McMullen). In the late 1800s some cruising adventurers converted fishing vessels and pilot boats into cruising boats. The most note of these was [[Joshua Slocum|Joshua Slocum's]] ''[[Spray (sailing vessel)|Spray]]'', a converted work boat in which he accomplished the first single-handed circumnavigation.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the 20th century, cruising yacht design evolved past the handicapping rules-based designs of the 19th century towards more sea-kindly hull designs. In the 1930s yacht hulls were designed with a \"fisherman\" underbody, whereby the slope of the bow continued to the fullest extent of the draft and then carried horizontally aft. Noted yacht designers, such as [[John Alden (naval architect)|John Alden]] and [[William Starling Burgess|Starling Burgess]] employed this configuration. Starting in the 1920s several new rating rules were devised by the [[Cruising Club of America]] and the [[Royal Ocean Racing Club]] in order to handicap yachts of different designs that were expected to compete against one another. Successful designers of this era were [[Olin Stephens]], [[Philip Rhodes]], Aage Nielson, and C. Raymond Hunt. The International Offshore Racing (IOR) rule supplanted the previous rules in 1970 to provide a fairer basis for handicapping racing yachts. This rule promoted the use of fin keels and blade rudders. This rule was augmented with the International Measurement System (IMS) to assure safe designs for extreme conditions, following the disastrous [[1979 Fastnet race|1979 Fastnet Race]] in which only 86 of the 303 participants finished owing to failed equipment and loss of 19 lives and five boats.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Technical Committee|first=Cruising Club of America|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/14377959|title=Desirable and undesirable characteristics of offshore yachts|date=1987|publisher=W.W. Norton|others=|year=|isbn=0-393-03311-2|editor-last=Rousmaniere|editor-first=John|location=New York|pages=23-39|oclc=14377959}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Larsson, Lars.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/864139368|title=Principles of yacht design|others=Eliasson, Rolf E.|isbn=978-1-4729-0555-0|edition=Third edition|location=London|oclc=864139368}}</ref>\n\n==Cruising==\n{{Under construction}}\n\nCruising yachts may be designed for near-shore use or for passage-making. They may also be raced, but they are designed and built with the comfort and amenities necessary for overnight voyages. Qualities considered in cruising yachts include: performance, comfort under way, ease of handling, stability, living comfort, durability, ease of maintenance, affordability of ownership.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Association|first=Royal Yachting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WmSbDwAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=sailing+yacht+insurance+categories&hl=en|title=RYA Offshore Sailing (E-G87)|last2=McClary|first2=Dick|date=2019-06-04|publisher=Royal Yachting Association|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Categories ===\nCruising sailboats share the common attribute of providing overnight accommodations. They may be classified as small (easy to haul behind a trailer),<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Henkel|first=Steve|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQt-0KvDJJkC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Cruising+sailboat&hl=en|title=The Sailor's Book of Small Cruising Sailboats: Reviews and Comparisons of 360 Boats Under 26 Feet|date=2010-01-15|publisher=McGraw Hill Professional|isbn=978-0-07-173694-7|language=en}}</ref> near-shore<ref name=\":1\" /> and off-shore.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Committee|first=Cruising Club of America Technical|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pee1lKH4J4kC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Cruising+sailboat&hl=en|title=Desirable and Undesirable Characteristics of Offshore Yachts|date=1987|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=978-0-393-03311-3|language=en}}</ref> Multihull sailing yachts are a category, apart.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Judges panel|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mo9Kw2sX9sC&pg=PA147&dq=cruising+sailing+yacht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiN6rro5PXoAhWlhHIEHQ9qAgsQ6AEwBHoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=Category&f=false|title=Boats of the Year|date=March 1997|work=Cruising World|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=90-100|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*'''Small''' \u2013 The sailing context for these cruisers is <u>sheltered</u> coastal waters, bays inlets, lakes and rivers.<ref name=\":5\" /> Small sailing yachts that are readily towed by a car are generally shorter than {{Convert|25|ft|m|abbr=}}, length overall and weigh less than {{Convert|5,000|lb|kg|abbr=}}.<ref name=\":2\" /> They are sometimes called \"pocket cruisers\" and may be [[trimaran]]s with folding [[Outrigger|outriggers]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Warren|first=Quentin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mo9Kw2sX9sC&pg=PA147&dq=cruising+sailing+yacht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiN6rro5PXoAhWlhHIEHQ9qAgsQ6AEwBHoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=pocket%20cruiser&f=false|title=Dragon 920 Swing Wing|date=July 1997|work=Cruising World|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=76|language=en}}</ref> Considerations for their design include: a shallow draft for launching, likely supplemented by a centerboard for performance under sail, sail area/displacement ratio as a measure of stability, displacement/length ratio as a measure of efficiency in propelling it through the water, and by its interior space\u2014both interior height and volume.<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[Royal Yachting Association]] (RYA) design category \"D\" addresses yachts that are fit for wind force 4\u2014{{Convert|16|kn|m/s|abbr=}}\u2014and {{Convert|0.5|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip|adj=on}} maximum wave heights.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n*'''Near-shore''' \u2013 The sailing context for these cruisers is <u>exposed</u> coastal waters, bays inlets, lakes and rivers.<ref name=\":5\" /> Near-shore cruising sailboats typically range in size from {{Convert|33-45|ft|m|abbr=}} length overall.<ref name=\":4\" /> The The RYA design category \"C\" addresses yachts that are fit for wind force 6\u2014{{Convert|27|kn|m/s|abbr=}}\u2014and {{Convert|2|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip|adj=on}} wave heights.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Association|first=Royal Yachting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oGqADwAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=sailing+yacht+insurance+categories&hl=en|title=RYA Stability & Buoyancy (E-G23)|date=2018-12-20|publisher=Royal Yachting Association|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*'''Offshore''' \u2013 The sailing context for these cruisers is offshore waters and extended voyages.<ref name=\":5\" /> Offshore cruising sailboats typically exceed {{Convert|45|ft|m|abbr=}} length overall.<ref name=\":4\" /> The RYA has two design categories for yachts used in this context: \"A\" yachts are fit for conditions that <u>exceed</u> wind force 8\u2014{{Convert|40|kn|m/s|abbr=}}\u2014and {{Convert|4|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip|adj=on}} wave heights. \"B\" yachts are fit for <u>up to</u> that threshold.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Design ===\nDesign considerations for a cruising yacht include seaworthiness, performance, sea kindliness, and cost of construction, as follows:<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n* ''Seaworthiness'' addresses the integrity of the vessel and its ability to stay afloat and shelter its crew in the conditions encountered. Watertightness of connections, ports and hatches are key to staying afloat. [[Metacentric height|Stability]]\u2014the ability to return to an upright condition when upset by waves is another key aspect.\n* ''Performance'' hinges on a number of factors, including the waterline length (longer means faster), drag in the water (narrower hull with smooth appendages), hull shape, and sail shape and area.\n* ''Sea kindliness'' is an indicator of steering ease, directional stability and quelling of motion induced by wind and waves.\n\nThe displacement of a monohull cruising sailboat affects the above factors, as follows:<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n* ''Heavy displacement'' yachts with a displacement to length (D/L) ratio of 400+ have a long, deep keel and a protected propellor. They are stable, often roomy, are resistant to harm from groundings and floating obstacles, and have good sea kindliness, but lack speed.\n* ''Medium displacement'' yachts with a D/L ratio of about 300 typically have a separate keel and blended rudder support, which improves speed and maneuverability over the heavy displacement designs.\n* ''Light displacement'' yachts with a D/L ratio of about 200 typically have a fin keel and a spade rudder with a ballasted bulb. They have good speed, maneuverability, and ability to point into the wind. Their sea kindliness is less than the heavy and medium-displacement categories.\n\nMultihulls offer tradeoffs as cruising sailboats, compared with [[Monohull|monohulls]]. They may be catamarans or trimarans. They rely on form stability\u2014having separate hulls far apart\u2014for their resistance to capsize.<ref name=\":6\" /> Their advantages include greater: stability, speed, (for catamarans) living space, and shallower draft. Their drawbacks include: greater expenses, greater [[windage]], more difficult tacking under sail, less load capacity, and more maneuvering room required because of their broad beam. They come with a variety of sleeping accommodations and (for catamarans) bridge-deck configurations. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Tarjan, Gregor.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/233534126|title=Catamarans : the complete guide for cruising sailors|date=2008|publisher=International Marine|isbn=978-0-07-159622-0|location=Camden, Me.|oclc=233534126}}</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\n\n=== Rigs ===\n\n=== Gear ===\n\n=== Accommodations ===\n\n=== Systems ===\n\n==Racing==\n{{Under construction|section=Description|placedby=HopsonRoad}}\nWorld Sailing recognizes nine classes of racing yacht:<ref>[http://www.sailing.org/classes/#isaf_sliding_tab_item_classes_index_yacht World Sailing classes of yachts].</ref>\n\n#[[Class40]]\n#[[Farr 30]]\n#[[Farr 40]]\n#[[International Maxi Association]]\n#[[J/111]]\n#[[IMOCA 60]]\n#[[Soto 40]]\n#[[Swan 45]]\n#[[Swan 60]]\n#[[TP 52]]\n#[[X-35 (yacht)|X-35]]\n#[[X-41 (yacht)|X-41]]\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscat-inline|Sailing yachts}}\n*[[Dinghy sailing]]\n*[[International class]]\n*[[List of large sailing yachts]]\n*[[Skiff|Sailing skiff]]\n{{International Sailing Federation Classes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Sailing yachts]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 400\n\n | image1 = 2013_Ahmanson_Cup_Regatta_yacht_Zapata_II_b_photo_D_Ramey_Logan.jpg\n | alt1 = A cruising yacht\n | caption1 = A 50&nbsp;ft cruising yacht\n\n | image2 = 60feet IMOCA SAFRAN 01.JPG\n | alt2 = A racing yacht\n | caption2 = A 60&nbsp;ft [[IMOCA 60|IMOCA]] ocean racing yacht\n\n | footer = Cruising and racing yachts embody different tradeoffs between comfort and performance.\n}}\n\nA '''sailing yacht''' (US ship prefixes SY or S/Y), is a leisure craft that uses sails as its primary means of propulsion. A yacht may be a sail or power vessel used for pleasure, cruising, or racing.<ref name=\"Webster\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/yacht|title=Definition of YACHT|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/us/dictionary/english/yacht|title=YACHT {{!}} definition in the Cambridge English Dictionary|website=dictionary.cambridge.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/us/dictionary/english/yacht|title=Yacht definition and meaning {{!}} Collins English Dictionary|website=www.collinsdictionary.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> There is no standard definition, so the term applies here to sailing vessels that have a cabin with amenities that accommodate overnight use. To be termed a \"yacht\", as opposed to a \"boat\", such a vessel is likely to be at least {{Convert|33|ft|m|abbr=}} in length and have been judged to have good aesthetic qualities.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boats.com/on-the-water/when-is-a-boat-also-a-yacht/|title=When is a Boat Also a Yacht? - boats.com|last=Kavin|first=Kim|date=June 4, 2018|website=www.boats.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> [[Sailboat|Sailboats]] that don't accommodate overnight use or are smaller than {{Convert|30|ft|m|abbr=}} are not universally called yachts. Sailing yachts in excess of {{Convert|40|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip}} are generally considered to be [[Superyacht|superyachts]].<ref name=\"Perry\">{{Cite book|last=Perry, Julie|title=Insiders' guide to becoming a yacht stewardess : confessions from my years afloat with the rich and famous|date=August 2013|isbn=978-1-61448-786-9|edition=Second|location=New York|oclc=859781233}}</ref>\n\nSailing [[yacht]]s are actively used in sport and are among categories recognized by the governing body of sailing sports, [[World Sailing]].<ref>[http://www.sailing.org/classes/#isaf_sliding_tab_item_classes_index_yacht World Sailing classes of yachts].</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe history of pleasure boats begins with rowed craft in Pharaonic Egyptian times. The history of sailing yachts begins in Europe in the beginning of the 1600s with the building of a pleasure vessel for the son of [[James VI and I|King James I of England]]. Pleasure vessels acquired the name ''yacht'' after the time of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], who spent time exiled in Europe and visited the Netherlands, where a variety of yachts (''jaghts'' in Dutch) were already well-developed as pleasure boats for the elite classes since the beginning of the 17th century. Upon his restoration to the English crown, Charles commissioned a series of royal yachts, which included at least one experimental [[catamaran]]. The first recorded yacht race between two vessels occurred in 1661, followed by the first open sailing competition in 1663 in English waters.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Herreshoff|first=L. Francis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q4RONp_1mrMC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=history+of+sailing+yachts&hl=en|title=The Golden Age of Yachting|date=2007|publisher=Sheridan House, Inc.|year=|isbn=978-1-57409-251-6|location=|pages=19-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 1739, England found itself in a series of wars\u2014a period that saw a decline in yachting. In Ireland, however, the gentry enjoyed yachting and founded the first yacht club in Cork as the Cork Harbor Water Club in 1720. English yacht racing continued among the English gentry who founded England's oldest yacht club in 1775 to support a fleet at [[Cumberland]]. With maritime peace, starting in 1815, came a resurgence of interest in yachting. Boatbuilders, who had been making fast vessels both for smugglers and the government [[Cutter (boat)|revenue cutters]], turned their skills again to yachts.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Evolution of design ===\nThe fast yachts of the early 19th century were typically [[lugger]]s, [[schooner]]s, or [[sloop]]s with [[fore-and-aft rig]]s. By the 1850s, yachts featured large sail areas, a narrow beam, and a deeper draft than was customary until then. Racing between yachts owned by wealthy patrons was common, with large wagers at stake. The [[America's Cup]] arose out of a contest between the yacht, ''[[America (yacht)|America]]'', and its English competitors. Both countries had rules by which to rate yachts, the English by tonnage and the American by length.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nEnglish and American design philosophies for sailing yachts diverged in the early 1800s: the English favoring a narrow [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] (width) and a deep-draft keel and the Americans favoring a broad beam and a shallow draft with a moveable centerboard to provide lateral resistance and righting moment. In 1851, when the yacht ''America'' crossed to England, the two design philosophies were converging back towards each other. ''America's'' pointed, convex bow and maximum beam, placed aft, influenced British designs, thanks to her racing successes against the British competition. American yachtsmen, in turn, found that their shallow \"skimming-dish\" designs weren't faster or safer than the visiting English yachts.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Doane, Charles J.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/551161085|title=The modern cruising sailboat : a complete guide to its design, construction, and outfitting|date=2010|publisher=International Marine|isbn=978-0-07-163700-8|location=Camden, Me.|oclc=551161085}}</ref>\n\nBy the turn of the 20th century, racing yachts featured long overhangs, fore and aft, and a narrow, deep keel by historic standards. Along the way, yacht designers discovered that handicapping rules based on tonnage or length were not good indicators of performance, although they remained a basis for taxation in the two home countries.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Cruising yachts ===\nThe prevalent purpose of yachting under sail in the 19th was racing. Boats would cross the Atlantic to engage the yachts of other owners in contests of speed. Cruising was the provenance of the most wealthy in large, luxurious yachts that had reliable auxiliary power or were solely steam-powered yachts.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEarly explorers in smaller sailing craft wrote of their experiences cruising the lakes and canals of Europe in a sailing canoe ([[John MacGregor (sportsman)|John MacGregor]]) and the near-shore waters of England and Scotland in a {{Convert|20|ft|m|abbr=|adj=on}} [[Cutter (boat)|cutter]] (R.T. McMullen). In the late 1800s some cruising adventurers converted fishing vessels and pilot boats into cruising boats. The most note of these was [[Joshua Slocum|Joshua Slocum's]] ''[[Spray (sailing vessel)|Spray]]'', a converted work boat in which he accomplished the first single-handed circumnavigation.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the 20th century, cruising yacht design evolved past the handicapping rules-based designs of the 19th century towards more sea-kindly hull designs. In the 1930s yacht hulls were designed with a \"fisherman\" underbody, whereby the slope of the bow continued to the fullest extent of the draft and then carried horizontally aft. Noted yacht designers, such as [[John Alden (naval architect)|John Alden]] and [[William Starling Burgess|Starling Burgess]] employed this configuration. Starting in the 1920s several new rating rules were devised by the [[Cruising Club of America]] and the [[Royal Ocean Racing Club]] in order to handicap yachts of different designs that were expected to compete against one another. Successful designers of this era were [[Olin Stephens]], [[Philip Rhodes]], Aage Nielson, and C. Raymond Hunt. The International Offshore Racing (IOR) rule supplanted the previous rules in 1970 to provide a fairer basis for handicapping racing yachts. This rule promoted the use of fin keels and blade rudders. This rule was augmented with the International Measurement System (IMS) to assure safe designs for extreme conditions, following the disastrous [[1979 Fastnet race|1979 Fastnet Race]] in which only 86 of the 303 participants finished owing to failed equipment and loss of 19 lives and five boats.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Technical Committee|first=Cruising Club of America|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/14377959|title=Desirable and undesirable characteristics of offshore yachts|date=1987|publisher=W.W. Norton|others=|year=|isbn=0-393-03311-2|editor-last=Rousmaniere|editor-first=John|location=New York|pages=23-39|oclc=14377959}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Larsson, Lars.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/864139368|title=Principles of yacht design|others=Eliasson, Rolf E.|isbn=978-1-4729-0555-0|edition=Third edition|location=London|oclc=864139368}}</ref>\n\n==Cruising==\n{{Under construction}}\n\nCruising yachts may be designed for near-shore use or for passage-making. They may also be raced, but they are designed and built with the comfort and amenities necessary for overnight voyages. Qualities considered in cruising yachts include: performance, comfort under way, ease of handling, stability, living comfort, durability, ease of maintenance, affordability of ownership.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Association|first=Royal Yachting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WmSbDwAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=sailing+yacht+insurance+categories&hl=en|title=RYA Offshore Sailing (E-G87)|last2=McClary|first2=Dick|date=2019-06-04|publisher=Royal Yachting Association|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Categories ===\nCruising sailboats share the common attribute of providing overnight accommodations. They may be classified as small (easy to haul behind a trailer),<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Henkel|first=Steve|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQt-0KvDJJkC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Cruising+sailboat&hl=en|title=The Sailor's Book of Small Cruising Sailboats: Reviews and Comparisons of 360 Boats Under 26 Feet|date=2010-01-15|publisher=McGraw Hill Professional|isbn=978-0-07-173694-7|language=en}}</ref> near-shore<ref name=\":1\" /> and off-shore.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Committee|first=Cruising Club of America Technical|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pee1lKH4J4kC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Cruising+sailboat&hl=en|title=Desirable and Undesirable Characteristics of Offshore Yachts|date=1987|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=978-0-393-03311-3|language=en}}</ref> Multihull sailing yachts are a category, apart.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Judges panel|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mo9Kw2sX9sC&pg=PA147&dq=cruising+sailing+yacht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiN6rro5PXoAhWlhHIEHQ9qAgsQ6AEwBHoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=Category&f=false|title=Boats of the Year|date=March 1997|work=Cruising World|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=90-100|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*'''Small''' \u2013 The sailing context for these cruisers is <u>sheltered</u> coastal waters, bays inlets, lakes and rivers.<ref name=\":5\" /> Small sailing yachts that are readily towed by a car are generally shorter than {{Convert|25|ft|m|abbr=}}, length overall and weigh less than {{Convert|5,000|lb|kg|abbr=}}.<ref name=\":2\" /> They are sometimes called \"pocket cruisers\" and may be [[trimaran]]s with folding [[Outrigger|outriggers]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Warren|first=Quentin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mo9Kw2sX9sC&pg=PA147&dq=cruising+sailing+yacht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiN6rro5PXoAhWlhHIEHQ9qAgsQ6AEwBHoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=pocket%20cruiser&f=false|title=Dragon 920 Swing Wing|date=July 1997|work=Cruising World|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=76|language=en}}</ref> Considerations for their design include: a shallow draft for launching, likely supplemented by a centerboard for performance under sail, sail area/displacement ratio as a measure of stability, displacement/length ratio as a measure of efficiency in propelling it through the water, and by its interior space\u2014both interior height and volume.<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[Royal Yachting Association]] (RYA) design category \"D\" addresses yachts that are fit for wind force 4\u2014{{Convert|16|kn|m/s|abbr=}}\u2014and {{Convert|0.5|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip|adj=on}} maximum wave heights.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n*'''Near-shore''' \u2013 The sailing context for these cruisers is <u>exposed</u> coastal waters, bays inlets, lakes and rivers.<ref name=\":5\" /> Near-shore cruising sailboats typically range in size from {{Convert|33-45|ft|m|abbr=}} length overall.<ref name=\":4\" /> The The RYA design category \"C\" addresses yachts that are fit for wind force 6\u2014{{Convert|27|kn|m/s|abbr=}}\u2014and {{Convert|2|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip|adj=on}} wave heights.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Association|first=Royal Yachting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oGqADwAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=sailing+yacht+insurance+categories&hl=en|title=RYA Stability & Buoyancy (E-G23)|date=2018-12-20|publisher=Royal Yachting Association|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*'''Offshore''' \u2013 The sailing context for these cruisers is offshore waters and extended voyages.<ref name=\":5\" /> Offshore cruising sailboats typically exceed {{Convert|45|ft|m|abbr=}} length overall.<ref name=\":4\" /> The RYA has two design categories for yachts used in this context: \"A\" yachts are fit for conditions that <u>exceed</u> wind force 8\u2014{{Convert|40|kn|m/s|abbr=}}\u2014and {{Convert|4|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip|adj=on}} wave heights. \"B\" yachts are fit for <u>up to</u> that threshold.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Design ===\nDesign considerations for a cruising yacht include seaworthiness, performance, sea kindliness, and cost of construction, as follows:<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n* ''Seaworthiness'' addresses the integrity of the vessel and its ability to stay afloat and shelter its crew in the conditions encountered. Watertightness of connections, ports and hatches are key to staying afloat. [[Metacentric height|Stability]]\u2014the ability to return to an upright condition when upset by waves is another key aspect.\n* ''Performance'' hinges on a number of factors, including the waterline length (longer means faster), drag in the water (narrower hull with smooth appendages), hull shape, and sail shape and area.\n* ''Sea kindliness'' is an indicator of steering ease, directional stability and quelling of motion induced by wind and waves.\n\nThe displacement of a monohull cruising sailboat affects the above factors, as follows:<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n* ''Heavy displacement'' yachts with a displacement to length (D/L) ratio of 400+ have a long, deep keel and a protected propellor. They are stable, often roomy, are resistant to harm from groundings and floating obstacles, and have good sea kindliness, but lack speed.\n* ''Medium displacement'' yachts with a D/L ratio of about 300 typically have a separate keel and blended rudder support, which improves speed and maneuverability over the heavy displacement designs.\n* ''Light displacement'' yachts with a D/L ratio of about 200 typically have a fin keel and a spade rudder with a ballasted bulb. They have good speed, maneuverability, and ability to point into the wind. Their sea kindliness is less than the heavy and medium-displacement categories.\n\nMultihulls offer tradeoffs as cruising sailboats, compared with [[Monohull|monohulls]]. They may be catamarans or trimarans. They rely on form stability\u2014having separate hulls far apart\u2014for their resistance to capsize.<ref name=\":6\" /> Their advantages include greater: stability, speed, (for catamarans) living space, and shallower draft. Their drawbacks include: greater expenses, greater [[windage]], more difficult tacking under sail, less load capacity, and more maneuvering room required because of their broad beam. They come with a variety of sleeping accommodations and (for catamarans) bridge-deck configurations. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Tarjan, Gregor.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/233534126|title=Catamarans : the complete guide for cruising sailors|date=2008|publisher=International Marine|isbn=978-0-07-159622-0|location=Camden, Me.|oclc=233534126}}</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\n\n=== Rigs ===\n\n=== Gear ===\n\n=== Accommodations ===\n\n=== Systems ===\n\n==Racing==\n{{Under construction|section=Description|placedby=HopsonRoad}}\nWorld Sailing recognizes nine classes of racing yacht:<ref>[http://www.sailing.org/classes/#isaf_sliding_tab_item_classes_index_yacht World Sailing classes of yachts].</ref>\n\n#[[Class40]]\n#[[Farr 30]]\n#[[Farr 40]]\n#[[International Maxi Association]]\n#[[J/111]]\n#[[IMOCA 60]]\n#[[Soto 40]]\n#[[Swan 45]]\n#[[Swan 60]]\n#[[TP 52]]\n#[[X-35 (yacht)|X-35]]\n#[[X-41 (yacht)|X-41]]\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscat-inline|Sailing yachts}}\n*[[Dinghy sailing]]\n*[[International class]]\n*[[List of large sailing yachts]]\n*[[Skiff|Sailing skiff]]\n{{International Sailing Federation Classes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Sailing yachts]]\n", "name_user": "HopsonRoad", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:convert", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sailing_yacht"}
{"title_page": "Walter Ciszek", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox saint\n|honorific_prefix=[[Servant of God]] \n|name=Walter Ciszek\n|honorific_suffix=[[Jesuits|S.J.]]\n|birth_date= November 4, 1904\n|birth_name = Walter Joseph Ciszek\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1984|12|8|1904|11|4}}\n|image=\n|imagesize=200px\n|caption=\n|birth_place= [[Shenandoah, Pennsylvania]], United States\n|death_place=[[Bronx]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n}}\n\n'''Walter Joseph Ciszek''' (November 4, 1904 &ndash; December 8, 1984) was a [[Polish-American]] [[Jesuit]] [[priest]] who conducted  [[Clandestine operation|clandestine]] [[missionary]] work in the [[Soviet Union]] between 1939 and 1963.\n\nFifteen of these years were spent in [[incarceration|confinement]] and [[hard labor]] in the [[Gulag]], plus five preceding them<ref name=ciszek/> in [[Moscow]]'s infamous [[Lubyanka prison]]. He was released and returned to the [[United States]] in 1963, after which he wrote two books, including the [[memoir]] ''[[With God in Russia]]'', and served as a spiritual director.\n\nSince 1990, Ciszek's life has been under consideration by the [[Roman Catholic Church]] for possible [[beatification]] or [[canonization]]. His current title is [[Servant of God]].\n\n==Early life and studies==\nCiszek was born on November 4, 1904, in the mining town of [[Shenandoah, Pennsylvania]], to Polish immigrants Mary (Mika) and Martin Ciszek,  who had emigrated to the [[United States]] in the 1890s.<ref name=league/> A former gang member, he shocked his family by deciding to become a priest. Ciszek entered the Jesuit [[novitiate]] in [[Poughkeepsie (city), New York|Poughkeepsie]], [[New York State|New York]] in 1928. The following year, he volunteered to serve as a missionary to Russia, which had become the Soviet Union after the [[Bolshevik Revolution]] 12 years before. Many religious rights for Soviet residents were [[Soviet anti-religious legislation|curtailed]], religious believers were openly [[Persecution of Christians in the Soviet Union| persecuted]], and few religious believers had access to the services of a priest. Pope [[Pius XI]] made an appeal to priests from around the world to go to Russia as missionaries.<ref name=league>[http://www.ciszek.org/About_Ciszek.html \"About Father Ciszek\", the Father Walter Ciszek Prayer League]</ref>\n\nIn 1934, Ciszek was sent to [[Rome]] to study [[theology]] and [[Russian language|Russian]], the [[history of Russia]] and [[Eastern Catholicism|liturgy]] at the Pontifical Russian College (or '[[Russicum]]'). In 1937, he was ordained a [[priest]] in the [[Byzantine Rite]] in Rome taking the name of Vladimir (see [[Russian Greek Catholic Church]]).<ref>Members of the Byzantine Rite [[Russian Catholic Church]], like members of other [[Eastern Catholic Churches]], are in [[full communion]] with the [[Roman Catholic Church]] but differ in rites, customs and canon law from the western, or Latin Rite Catholic Church. The majority of Catholics in Russia have always been members of the Latin Rite church, however.</ref>\n\nIn 1938, Ciszek was sent to the Jesuit mission in Albertyn in eastern [[Poland]].<ref name=league/> With  the outbreak of [[World War II]] in 1939, the [[Soviet Union]] occupied eastern Poland and forced Ciszek to close his mission. Arriving in [[Lviv]], he realized that it would be very easy for a priest or two to enter the Soviet Union amid the streams of exiles going East. After securing the permission of [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan]] [[Andrei Sheptytsky]], he crossed the border in 1940 under the assumed identity of ''W\u0142adymyr \u0141ypynski''. With two of his fellow Jesuits, he travelled {{convert|2400|km}} by train to the logging town of [[Chusovoy]], in the [[Ural Mountains]]. For one year, he worked as an unskilled logger, while discreetly performing religious ministry at the same time.\n\n==Captivity in the Soviet Union==\n{{Modern persecutions of the Catholic Church}}\nCiszek was arrested in 1941 under accusations of [[espionage]] for the [[Holy See|Vatican]] and sent to the [[Lubyanka prison]] in Moscow, operated by the [[NKVD]] (internal security agency). There he spent a total of five years, most of which in [[solitary confinement]]. In 1942, he signed a [[Confession (religion)|confession]] under severe torture. He was convicted of [[espionage]] and  [[Sentence (law)|sentenced]] to 15 years hard labor in the GULAG.\n\nCiszek was to remain in Lubyanka for four more years. In 1946, he was sent by train to [[Krasnoyarsk]] then 20 days by boat to [[Norilsk]] in [[Siberia]]. There, he was to shovel coal onto [[Cargo ship|freighter]] [[Ship|vessels]], and later transferred to work in [[coal mine]]s. A year later, he was sent to work in construction at an ore processing plant. From 1953 to 1955, he worked in mines. His memoirs provide a vivid description of the revolts that spread through the GULAG in the aftermath of [[Joseph Stalin]]'s death (see [[Norilsk uprising]]).\n\nThroughout his lengthy imprisonment, Ciszek continued to pray, to celebrate [[Divine Liturgy]], hear [[Confession (religion)|confession]]s, conduct [[Retreat (spiritual)|retreat]]s and perform parish ministry. Until he was allowed to write to America in 1955, he was presumed dead by both his family and the Jesuit Order.\n\nBy April 22, 1955, Ciszek's hard labor sentence was complete, and he was released with restrictions in the city of Norilsk. At this time, he was finally able to write to his sisters in the United States.\n\nCiszek was ordered by the [[KGB]] to move in 1958 to Krasnoyarsk, where he secretly established mission parishes. After the KGB learned of this, he was forcibly transferred to [[Abakan]], {{convert|160|km}} to the south, where he worked as an automobile mechanic for four more years. In 1963, he finally received a letter from his sisters in the U.S. Several months later, the Soviet Union decided to return him (and an American student [[Marvin W. Makinen]]) to the United States in exchange for two Soviet agents. He was not informed of this until he was delivered to an official of the [[U.S. State Department]] and told he was still an American citizen.\n\n==Release and later life==\n{{Jesuit}}\nAfter nearly 23 years of imprisonment, Ciszek was released with American student [[Marvin Makinen]] on October 12, 1963, in exchange for two Soviet agents (Ivan Egorov, a Soviet U.N. functionary, and his wife Alexandra, arrested for espionage in July). After his return, he is quoted as stating, \"I am an American, happy to be home; but in many ways I am almost a stranger.\"  In 1965, he began working and lecturing at the John XXIII Center at [[Fordham University]] (now the Center for Eastern Christian Studies at the [[University of Scranton]] in [[Scranton]], [[Pennsylvania]]), counseling and offering spiritual direction to those who visited him, until his death.\n\nOn December 8, 1984, Ciszek died after many years of declining health, and was [[burial|buried]] at the Jesuit Cemetery in [[Wernersville]], [[Pennsylvania]].\n\n[[Image:Walter ciszek tomb 2004.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Walter Ciszek's grave at the Jesuit Center in Wernersville, Pennsylvania.]]\n\n==Legacy==\nNine audio tapes of interviews conducted with Ciszek (ca. 1964) remain at [[Georgetown University]].\n\nIn 1985, a [[Carmelite]] [[nun]], Mother Marija, who was the [[:wikt:mother superior|mother superior]] of a [[Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church|Ruthenian Rite]] Carmelite monastery which Fr. Ciszek helped found, and formerly under his spiritual direction, began to petition for official recognition of Fr. Ciszek and his work within the Catholic Church. In 1990, Bishop Michael J. Dudick of the [[Eparchy]] of [[Passaic, New Jersey]], opened an official diocesan process of investigation for official recognition on the road to beatification, a step toward possible [[canonization]] as a [[saint]]. His case is currently being handled by the [[Diocese]] of [[Allentown, Pennsylvania]].\n\nCiszek Hall at [[Fordham University]] in [[New York City]] is named after Fr. Ciszek. It currently houses Jesuit scholastics in the first stage of formal study for the priesthood. Additionally, a small room has been set aside in honor of Fr. Ciszek.  It contains the (Latin) altar, sacred vessels, candle sticks, and crucifix Fr. Ciszek used, as well as a copy (in his own hand) of his final vows and a photocopy of a letter to a friend containing spiritual advice.  There is also a Ciszek Hall at the [[University of Scranton]]. Shenandoah, Pennsylvania also commemorated his legacy by the founding of a Catholic elementary school named Father Walter J. Ciszek School, later renamed Trinity Academy at the Father Walter J. Ciszek Education Center. [[Marquette University]]'s Walter Ciszek Collection is named for Fr. Ciszek, and is maintained by the university's [[Knights of Columbus]] council.  The collection is held in Raynor Memorial Library and contains various Catholic literature and video materials.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marquette.edu/library/about/ciszek.php}}</ref>  Additionally, the council sponsors an annual Ciszek Lecture at Marquette, which was established in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marquette.edu/news-center/2019/marquette-to-host-microsoft-chief-technology-officer-for-ciszek-lecture.php}}</ref>\n\n==Quotes==\n*The power of prayer reaches beyond all efforts of man seeking to find meaning in life. This power is available to all; it can transform man's weaknesses, limitations and his sufferings.<ref>[http://imagesofheaven.org/WalterCiszek.html Walter Ciszek, SJ Tribute by Images of Heaven<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Across that threshold I had been afraid to cross, things suddenly seemed so very simple. There was but a single vision, God, who was all in all; there was but one will that directed all things, God's will.  I had only to see it, to discern it in every circumstance in which I found myself, and let myself be ruled by it.  God is in all things, sustains all things, directs all things.  To discern this in every situation and circumstance, to see His will in all things, was to accept each circumstance and situation and let oneself be borne along in perfect confidence and trust.  Nothing could separate me from Him, because He was in all things. No danger could threaten me, no fear could shake me, except the fear of losing sight of Him.  The future, hidden as it was, was hidden in His will and therefore acceptable to me no matter what it might bring.  The past, with all its failures, was not forgotten; it remained to remind me of the weakness of human nature and the folly of putting any faith in self.  But it no longer depressed me.  I looked no longer to self to guide me, relied on it no longer in any way, so it could not again fail me. By renouncing, finally and completely, all control of my life and future destiny, I was relieved as a consequence of all responsibility. I was freed thereby from anxiety and worry, from every tension, and could float serenely upon the tide of God's sustaining providence in perfect peace of soul.<ref name=ciszek>{{cite book|last=Ciszek|first=Walter J.|title=He Leadeth Me|year=1973|publisher=Doubleday & Company, Inc.|location=Garden City, New York|isbn=0-89870-546-0|pages=79\u201380|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmdVjLpJ5HUC&lpg=PA79&vq=across%20the%20threshold&pg=PA79#v=onepage&q=across%20that%20threshold%20I%20had%20been%20afraid%20to%20cross&f=false}}</ref>\n*His will for us was in the twenty-four hours of each day: the people, the places, the circumstances He set before us in that time. Those were the things God knew were important to Him and to us at that moment, and those were the things upon which He wanted us to act.\n\n==Books==\n* ''With God in Russia'', (with Daniel L. Flaherty, S.J.), memoir (New York: McGraw-Hill, 1964).\n* ''He Leadeth Me'', (with Daniel L. Flaherty, S.J.), memoir (New York: Doubleday, 1973).\n* \"With God in America\", (published posthumously), memoir with primary sources (Chicago: Loyola Press, 2016).\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.library.georgetown.edu/dept/speccoll/cl191.htm Details of Ciszek materials] at [[Georgetown University]] library\n*[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,873742,00.html Time Magazine 1963 story on the release of Walter Ciszek]\n*[http://www.catechismclass.com/shop/lessons_detail.php?id=100 Summary of the Writings of Walter Ciszek]\n\n{{Persecution of Christians|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Canonization}}\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= United States |portal4= Saints}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ciszek, Walter}}\n[[Category:1904 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Shenandoah, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Polish Eastern Catholics]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:American Eastern Catholics]]\n[[Category:20th-century American Jesuits]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic writers]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Anti-Catholicism in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Victims of anti-Catholic violence]]\n[[Category:American people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:American people imprisoned in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:20th-century venerated Christians]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Russia]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Foreign Gulag detainees]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Eastern Catholic clergy]]\n[[Category:Jesuit Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Eastern Catholic Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Persecution by atheist states]]\n[[Category:Anti-Christian sentiment in Europe]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Participants in the Norilsk uprising]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox saint\n|honorific_prefix=[[Servant of God]] \n|name=Walter Ciszek\n|honorific_suffix=[[Jesuits|S.J.]]\n|birth_date= November 4, 1904\n|birth_name = Walter Joseph Ciszek\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1984|12|8|1904|11|4}}\n|image=\n|imagesize=200px\n|caption=\n|birth_place= [[Shenandoah, Pennsylvania]], United States\n|death_place=[[Bronx]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n}}\n\n'''Walter Joseph Ciszek''' (November 4, 1904 &ndash; December 8, 1984) was a [[Polish-American]] [[Jesuit]] [[priest]] who conducted  [[Clandestine operation|clandestine]] [[missionary]] work in the [[Soviet Union]] between 1939 and 1963.\n\nFifteen of these years were spent in [[incarceration|confinement]] and [[hard labor]] in the [[Gulag]], plus five preceding them<ref name=ciszek/> in [[Moscow]]'s infamous [[Lubyanka prison]]. He was released and returned to the [[United States]] in 1963, after which he wrote two books, including the [[memoir]] ''[[With God in Russia]]'', and served as a spiritual director.\n\nSince 1990, Ciszek's life has been under consideration by the [[Roman Catholic Church]] for possible [[beatification]] or [[canonization]]. His current title is [[Servant of God]].\n\n==Early life and studies==\nCiszek was born on November 4, 1904, in the mining town of [[Shenandoah, Pennsylvania]], to Polish immigrants Mary (Mika) and Martin Ciszek,  who had emigrated to the [[United States]] in the 1890s.<ref name=league/> A former gang member, he shocked his family by deciding to become a priest. Ciszek entered the Jesuit [[novitiate]] in [[Poughkeepsie (city), New York|Poughkeepsie]], [[New York State|New York]] in 1928. The following year, he volunteered to serve as a missionary to Russia, which had become the Soviet Union after the [[Bolshevik Revolution]] 12 years before. Many religious rights for Soviet residents were [[Soviet anti-religious legislation|curtailed]], religious believers were openly [[Persecution of Christians in the Soviet Union| persecuted]], and few religious believers had access to the services of a priest. Pope [[Pius XI]] made an appeal to priests from around the world to go to Russia as missionaries.<ref name=league>[http://www.ciszek.org/About_Ciszek.html \"About Father Ciszek\", the Father Walter Ciszek Prayer League]</ref>\n\nIn 1934, Ciszek was sent to [[Rome]] to study [[theology]] and [[Russian language|Russian]], the [[history of Russia]] and [[Eastern Catholicism|liturgy]] at the Pontifical Russian College (or '[[Russicum]]'). In 1937, he was ordained a [[priest]] in the [[Byzantine Rite]] in Rome taking the name of Vladimir (see [[Russian Greek Catholic Church]]).<ref>Members of the Byzantine Rite [[Russian Catholic Church]], like members of other [[Eastern Catholic Churches]], are in [[full communion]] with the [[Roman Catholic Church]] but differ in rites, customs and canon law from the western, or Latin Rite Catholic Church. The majority of Catholics in Russia have always been members of the Latin Rite church, however.</ref>\n\nIn 1938, Ciszek was sent to the Jesuit mission in Albertyn in eastern [[Poland]].<ref name=league/> With  the outbreak of [[World War II]] in 1939, the [[Soviet Union]] occupied eastern Poland and forced Ciszek to close his mission. Arriving in [[Lviv]], he realized that it would be very easy for a priest or two to enter the Soviet Union amid the streams of exiles going East. After securing the permission of [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan]] [[Andrei Sheptytsky]], he crossed the border in 1940 under the assumed identity of ''W\u0142adymyr \u0141ypynski''. With two of his fellow Jesuits, he travelled {{convert|2400|km}} by train to the logging town of [[Chusovoy]], in the [[Ural Mountains]]. For one year, he worked as an unskilled logger, while discreetly performing religious ministry at the same time.\n\n==Captivity in the Soviet Union==\n{{Modern persecutions of the Catholic Church}}\nCiszek was arrested in 1941 under accusations of [[espionage]] for the [[Holy See|Vatican]] and sent to the [[Lubyanka prison]] in Moscow, operated by the [[NKVD]] (internal security agency). There he spent a total of five years, most of which in [[solitary confinement]]. In 1942, he signed a [[Confession (religion)|confession]] under severe torture. He was convicted of [[espionage]] and  [[Sentence (law)|sentenced]] to 15 years hard labor in the GULAG.\n\nCiszek was to remain in Lubyanka for four more years. In 1946, he was sent by train to [[Krasnoyarsk]] then 20 days by boat to [[Norilsk]] in [[Siberia]]. There, he was to shovel coal onto [[Cargo ship|freighter]] [[Ship|vessels]], and later transferred to work in [[coal mine]]s. A year later, he was sent to work in construction at an ore processing plant. From 1953 to 1955, he worked in mines. His memoirs provide a vivid description of the revolts that spread through the GULAG in the aftermath of [[Joseph Stalin]]'s death (see [[Norilsk uprising]]).\n\nThroughout his lengthy imprisonment, Ciszek continued to pray, to celebrate [[Divine Liturgy]], hear [[Confession (religion)|confession]]s, conduct [[Retreat (spiritual)|retreat]]s and perform parish ministry. Until he was allowed to write to America in 1955, he was presumed dead by both his family and the Jesuit Order.\n\nBy April 22, 1955, Ciszek's hard labor sentence was complete, and he was released with restrictions in the city of Norilsk. At this time, he was finally able to write to his sisters in the United States.\n\nCiszek was ordered by the [[KGB]] to move in 1958 to Krasnoyarsk, where he secretly established mission parishes. After the KGB learned of this, he was forcibly transferred to [[Abakan]], {{convert|160|km}} to the south, where he worked as an automobile mechanic for four more years. In 1963, he finally received a letter from his sisters in the U.S. Several months later, the Soviet Union decided to return him (and an American student [[Marvin W. Makinen]]) to the United States in exchange for two Soviet agents. He was not informed of this until he was delivered to an official of the [[U.S. State Department]] and told he was still an American citizen.\n\n==Release and later life==\n{{Jesuit}}\nAfter nearly 23 years of imprisonment, Ciszek was released with American student [[Marvin Makinen]] on October 12, 1963, in exchange for two Soviet agents (Ivan Egorov, a Soviet U.N. functionary, and his wife Alexandra, arrested for espionage in July). After his return, he is quoted as stating, \"I am an American, happy to be home; but in many ways I am almost a stranger.\"  In 1965, he began working and lecturing at the John XXIII Center at [[Fordham University]] (now the Center for Eastern Christian Studies at the [[University of Scranton]] in [[Scranton]], [[Pennsylvania]]), counseling and offering spiritual direction to those who visited him, until his death.\n\nOn December 8, 1984, Ciszek died after many years of declining health, and was [[burial|buried]] at the Jesuit Cemetery in [[Wernersville]], [[Pennsylvania]].\n\n[[Image:Walter ciszek tomb 2004.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Walter Ciszek's grave at the Jesuit Center in Wernersville, Pennsylvania.]]\n\n==Legacy==\nNine audio tapes of interviews conducted with Ciszek (ca. 1964) remain at [[Georgetown University]].\n\nIn 1985, a [[Carmelite]] [[nun]], Mother Marija, who was the [[:wikt:mother superior|mother superior]] of a [[Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church|Ruthenian Rite]] Carmelite monastery which Fr. Ciszek helped found, and formerly under his spiritual direction, began to petition for official recognition of Fr. Ciszek and his work within the Catholic Church. In 1990, Bishop Michael J. Dudick of the [[Eparchy]] of [[Passaic, New Jersey]], opened an official diocesan process of investigation for official recognition on the road to beatification, a step toward possible [[canonization]] as a [[saint]]. His case is currently being handled by the [[Diocese]] of [[Allentown, Pennsylvania]].\n\nCiszek Hall at [[Fordham University]] in [[New York City]] is named after Fr. Ciszek. It currently houses Jesuit scholastics in the first stage of formal study for the priesthood. Additionally, a small room has been set aside in honor of Fr. Ciszek.  It contains the (Latin) altar, sacred vessels, candle sticks, and crucifix Fr. Ciszek used, as well as a copy (in his own hand) of his final vows and a photocopy of a letter to a friend containing spiritual advice.  There is also a Ciszek Hall at the [[University of Scranton]]. Shenandoah, Pennsylvania also commemorated his legacy by the founding of a Catholic elementary school named Father Walter J. Ciszek School, later renamed Trinity Academy at the Father Walter J. Ciszek Education Center. [[Marquette University]]'s Walter Ciszek Collection is named for Fr. Ciszek, and is maintained by the university's [[Knights of Columbus]] council.  The collection is held in Raynor Memorial Library and contains various Catholic literature and video materials.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marquette.edu/library/about/ciszek.php}}</ref>  Additionally, the council sponsors an annual Ciszek Lecture at Marquette, which was established in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marquette.edu/news-center/2019/marquette-to-host-microsoft-chief-technology-officer-for-ciszek-lecture.php}}</ref>\n\n==Quotes==\n*The power of prayer reaches beyond all efforts of man seeking to find meaning in life. This power is available to all; it can transform man's weaknesses, limitations and his sufferings.<ref>[http://imagesofheaven.org/WalterCiszek.html Walter Ciszek, SJ Tribute by Images of Heaven<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Across that threshold I had been afraid to cross, things suddenly seemed so very simple. There was but a single vision, God, who was all in all; there was but one will that directed all things, God's will.  I had only to see it, to discern it in every circumstance in which I found myself, and let myself be ruled by it.  God is in all things, sustains all things, directs all things.  To discern this in every situation and circumstance, to see His will in all things, was to accept each circumstance and situation and let oneself be borne along in perfect confidence and trust.  Nothing could separate me from Him, because He was in all things. No danger could threaten me, no fear could shake me, except the fear of losing sight of Him.  The future, hidden as it was, was hidden in His will and therefore acceptable to me no matter what it might bring.  The past, with all its failures, was not forgotten; it remained to remind me of the weakness of human nature and the folly of putting any faith in self.  But it no longer depressed me.  I looked no longer to self to guide me, relied on it no longer in any way, so it could not again fail me. By renouncing, finally and completely, all control of my life and future destiny, I was relieved as a consequence of all responsibility. I was freed thereby from anxiety and worry, from every tension, and could float serenely upon the tide of God's sustaining providence in perfect peace of soul.<ref name=ciszek>{{cite book|last=Ciszek|first=Walter J.|title=He Leadeth Me|year=1973|publisher=Doubleday & Company, Inc.|location=Garden City, New York|isbn=0-89870-546-0|pages=79\u201380|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmdVjLpJ5HUC&lpg=PA79&vq=across%20the%20threshold&pg=PA79#v=onepage&q=across%20that%20threshold%20I%20had%20been%20afraid%20to%20cross&f=false}}</ref>\n*His will for us was in the twenty-four hours of each day: the people, the places, the circumstances He set before us in that time. Those were the things God knew were important to Him and to us at that moment, and those were the things upon which He wanted us to act.\n\n==Books==\n* ''With God in Russia'', (with Daniel L. Flaherty, S.J.), memoir (New York: McGraw-Hill, 1964).\n* ''He Leadeth Me'', (with Daniel L. Flaherty, S.J.), memoir (New York: Doubleday, 1973).\n* \"With God in America\", (published posthumously), memoir with primary sources (Chicago: Loyola Press, 2016).\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.library.georgetown.edu/dept/speccoll/cl191.htm Details of Ciszek materials] at [[Georgetown University]] library\n*[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,873742,00.html Time Magazine 1963 story on the release of Walter Ciszek]\n*[http://www.catechismclass.com/shop/lessons_detail.php?id=100 Summary of the Writings of Walter Ciszek]\n\n{{Persecution of Christians|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Canonization}}\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= United States |portal4= Saints}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ciszek, Walter}}\n[[Category:1904 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Shenandoah, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Russian Greek-Catholics]]\n[[Category:Polish Eastern Catholics]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:American Eastern Catholics]]\n[[Category:20th-century American Jesuits]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic writers]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Anti-Catholicism in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Victims of anti-Catholic violence]]\n[[Category:American people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:American people imprisoned in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:20th-century venerated Christians]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Russia]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Foreign Gulag detainees]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Eastern Catholic clergy]]\n[[Category:Jesuit Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Eastern Catholic Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Persecution by atheist states]]\n[[Category:Anti-Christian sentiment in Europe]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Participants in the Norilsk uprising]]\n", "name_user": "Azmi1995", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Ciszek"}
{"title_page": "Matthew Broderick", "text_new": "{{short description|American film, stage and voice actor}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Matthew Broderick\n| image       = Matthew Broderick 2012.jpg\n| caption     = Broderick in 2012\n| birth_name  = Matthew John Broderick\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1962|3|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| occupation  = {{hlist|[[Actor]]|[[comedian]]|[[Singing|singer]]}}\n| years_active = 1981\u2013present\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Sarah Jessica Parker]]|May 19, 1997}}\n| children    = 3\n| father      = [[James Broderick]]\n| mother      = [[Patricia Broderick]]\n| relatives   = [[Milton H. Biow]] (grandfather)\n}}\n'''Matthew John Broderick''' (born March 21, 1962)<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Sim|first=David|title=MATTHEW BRODERICK'S BIRTHDAY: HIS 15 BEST MOVIES RANKED|date=21 March 2019|magazine=[[Newsweek]]|url=https://www.newsweek.com/matthew-broderick-birthday-best-movies-ranked-age-1369680|accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref> is an American actor, comedian and singer. His roles include the [[Golden Globe]]-nominated portrayal of the title character in ''[[Ferris Bueller's Day Off]]'' (1986), the voice of the adult [[Simba]] in [[Disney]]'s [[The Lion King (franchise)|''The Lion King'' trilogy]] (1994\u20132004), and [[Leo Bloom]] in both the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[The Producers (musical)|The Producers]]'' and its 2005 [[The Producers (2005 film)|film adaptation]]. Other films he had starring credits in include ''[[WarGames]]'' (1983), ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]'' (1989), ''[[The Freshman (1990 film)|The Freshman]]'' (1990), ''[[The Cable Guy]]'' (1996), ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]'' (1998), ''[[Election (1999 film)|Election]]'' (1999), ''[[Inspector Gadget (film)|Inspector Gadget]]'' (1999) and ''[[You Can Count on Me]]'' (2000).  Broderick also directed himself in ''[[Infinity (film)|Infinity]]'' (1996) and provided voice work in ''[[Good Boy!]]'' (2003), ''[[Bee Movie]]'' (2007), and ''[[The Tale of Despereaux (film)|The Tale of Despereaux]]'' (2008).\n\nBroderick has won two [[Tony Awards]], one for [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play|Best Featured Actor in a Play]] for ''[[Brighton Beach Memoirs]]'' (1983), and one for [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]] for ''[[How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying]]'' (1995).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/stars/matthew-broderick/profile/|title=Matthew Broderick Biography|work=Broadway.com|accessdate=March 14, 2014}}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, Broderick remains the youngest winner of the Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play.<ref>{{cite web|author= Nicholas Ephram Ryan Daniels|title=25 facts you probably didn't know about Matthew Broderick|date=15 July 2019|publisher=[[London Theatre Direct]]|url=https://www.londontheatredirect.com/news/25-facts-you-probably-didnt-know-about-matthew-broderick|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, for his contributions to the film industry, Matthew Broderick was inducted into the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] with a [[List of actors with Hollywood Walk of Fame motion picture stars|motion pictures star]] located at 6801 [[Hollywood Boulevard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/matthew-broderick |title=Hollywood Walk of Fame - Matthew Broderick |website=walkoffame.com |publisher=Hollywood Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=November 30, 2017}}</ref> Eleven years later, Broderick earned induction into the [[American Theater Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/audra-mcdonald-matthew-broderick-marin-mazzie-among-2017-theater-hall-of-fame-inductees|title=Audra McDonald, Matthew Broderick, Marin Mazzie among 2017 Theater Hall of Fame Inductees|publisher=www.playbill.com|accessdate=December 29, 2017}}</ref> Broderick starred as Michael Burr in the [[Netflix]] comedy series ''[[Daybreak (2019 TV series)|Daybreak]]'' (2019).\n\n==Early life and education==\nBroderick was born in [[Manhattan]], New York, the son of [[Patricia Broderick|Patricia]] ([[Married and maiden names|n\u00e9e]] Biow), a playwright, actress, and painter, and [[James Broderick]], an actor<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography: Patricia Broderick|url=http://www.tibordenagy.com/artists/broderick.html|publisher=Tibor de Nagy|year=2008|accessdate=May 19, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061216130646/http://www.tibordenagy.com/artists/broderick.html|archivedate=December 16, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and a [[World War II]] veteran.<ref name=huffingtonpost.com>{{cite web|last=Smolenyak|first=Megan|title=Matthew Broderick, Who Do You Think You Are?|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/megan-smolenyak-smolenyak/matthew-broderick-who-do-_b_825260.html|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=February 18, 2011}}</ref> His mother was [[Jewish]], a descendant of Jewish immigrants from Germany and Poland.<ref name=tca>Stated on ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]'', 2005</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Tugend|title=Bialystock and Bloom Tell the Truth|url=http://jewishjournal.com/culture/arts/12403/|work=JewishJournal|date=December 16, 2005|accessdate=May 19, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Nate|last=Bloom|url=http://www.stljewishlight.com/features/article_27d2ff80-db75-11e7-81ca-3346fc71e048.html|title='Tis the season for the Goldbergs to face the 'December Dilemma'|work=[[St. Louis Jewish Light]]|date=December 7, 2017|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Austin|last=O'Connor|url=https://www.aarp.org/entertainment/television/info-2017/matthew-broderick-interview-fd.html|title=Matthew Broderick's Christmas Presence|work=[[AARP]]|date=December 14, 2017|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Barbara|last=Hoffman|url=https://nypost.com/2018/04/19/matthew-broderick-cynthia-nixon-will-have-to-work-for-my-vote/|title=Matthew Broderick: Cynthia Nixon will have to work for my vote|work=[[New York Post]]|date=April 19, 2018|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=1429337|title=Excerpt: 'Stars of David : Prominent Jews Talk About Being Jewish' by Abigail Pogrebin|work=[[ABC News]]|date=December 26, 2005|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref> His father was a Catholic of Irish, and some English, descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.progenealogists.com/matthew-broderick-who-do-you-think-you-are.htm |title=Matthew Broderick: 'Who Do You Think You Are?'|first=Kyle J.|last=Betit|publisher=ProGenealogists|date=April 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413062601/http://www.progenealogists.com/matthew-broderick-who-do-you-think-you-are.htm|archivedate=April 13, 2010|url-status=live|accessdate=May 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Celia|last=McGee|title=Broderick's Set to Bloom in 'Producers'|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|date=April 18, 2001|url=http://www.matthewbroderick.net/article/nydaily01.html|via=Shinanat Mahamaytakit|accessdate=December 13, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116143804/http://matthewbroderick.net/article/nydaily01.html|archivedate=November 16, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Seal|first=Mark|title=Magical Mystery Tour|url=http://www.matthewbroderick.net/interview/americanway060101.html|work=American Way|date=January 1, 2006|via=Shinanat Mahamaytakit|accessdate=May 19, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517080611/http://www.matthewbroderick.net/interview/americanway060101.html|archivedate=May 17, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Broderick attended grade school at [[City and Country School]] in Manhattan and high school at the private [[Walden School (New York City)|Walden School]], also in [[Manhattan]].<ref name=fymb>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZmgaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RioEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2913%2C4478449|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]. Milwaukee Journal|title=For young Matthew Broderick, stage and movies are his campus|last=Kornbluth|first=Jesse|date=April 7, 1985|page=1, Entertainment}}</ref> He received acting training at [[HB Studio]].<ref>[https://hbstudio.org/about-hb-studio/alumni/ HB Studio Almuni]</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Matthew Broderick.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Broderick in Sweden during his promotion of ''[[Ferris Bueller's Day Off]]'']]\nBroderick's first major acting role came in an [[HB Studio]] workshop production of playwright [[Horton Foote]]'s ''On Valentine's Day'', playing opposite his father, who was a friend of Foote's. This was followed by a supporting role as [[Harvey Fierstein]]'s gay adopted son, David, in the [[Off-Broadway]] production of Fierstein's ''[[Torch Song Trilogy]]''; then, a good review by ''[[The New York Times]]'' theater critic [[Mel Gussow]] brought him to the attention of [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. Broderick commented on the effects of that review in a 2004 ''[[60 Minutes II]]'' interview:\n\n<blockquote>Before I knew it, I was like this guy in a hot play. And suddenly, all these doors opened. And it's only because Mel Gussow happened to come by right before it closed and happened to like it. It's just amazing. All these things have to line up that are out of your control.</blockquote>\n\nHe followed that with the role of Eugene Morris Jerome in the [[Neil Simon]] ''[[Eugene Trilogy]]'' including the plays ''[[Brighton Beach Memoirs]]'' and ''[[Biloxi Blues]]''. He won the [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play]] for his role in ''Brighton Beach Memoirs''.\n\nHis first film role was also written by Neil Simon. Broderick debuted in ''[[Max Dugan Returns]]'' (1983). His first big hit film was ''[[WarGames]]'', a summer hit in [[1983 in film|1983]],<ref name=tstbhl>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=eeIhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=JGMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6966%2C1801595|work=[[Pittsburgh Press]]|last=Siskel|first=Gene|title=Matthew Broderick toast of Broadway, Hollywood|date=July 19, 1983|page=A7}}</ref> in which he played the main role of David Lightman, a [[Seattle]] teen [[Hacker (term)|hacker]]. This was followed by the role of Philippe Gaston in ''[[Ladyhawke (film)|Ladyhawke]]'', in 1985.<ref name=fymb/><ref name=strstsc>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kkwyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cuUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6868%2C4657278|work=Lawrence Journal-World|location=Kansas|last=Thomas|first=Bob|title=Matthew Broderick has string of stage, screen successes|date=June 22, 1986|page=3D}}</ref>\n\nBroderick then won the role of the charming, clever slacker in the [[1986 in film|1986]] film ''[[Ferris Bueller's Day Off]]''. At the age of 23, Broderick played a high school student who, with his girlfriend and best friend, [[truant|plays hooky]] and explores [[Chicago]]. The film is a 1980s comedy favorite, and is one of Broderick's best known roles (particularly with teenage audiences).  Also in 1987, he played Air Force research assistant Jimmy Garrett in ''[[Project X (1987 film)|Project X]]''. In 1988, Broderick played [[Harvey Fierstein]]'s gay lover, Alan, in the screen adaptation of ''[[Torch Song Trilogy]]''.\n\nHe starred in the 1989 film ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]'' alongside [[Cary Elwes]], [[Morgan Freeman]], and [[Denzel Washington]], where he received favorable reviews for his portrayal of the [[American Civil War]] officer [[Robert Gould Shaw]], whom Broderick incidentally physically resembled at the time.\n\nIn the 1990s, Broderick was the voice of the adult [[Simba]], in Disney's successful animated film ''[[The Lion King]]'', and also voiced Tack the Cobbler in [[Miramax]]'s controversial version of ''[[The Thief and the Cobbler]]'', which had originally been intended as a silent role. He won recognition for two [[black comedy|dark comedy]] roles. The first was that of a bachelor in ''[[The Cable Guy]]'' with [[Jim Carrey]]. The second was that of a high school teacher in Alexander Payne's ''[[Election (1999 film)|Election]]'' with [[Reese Witherspoon]].\n\nBroderick returned to Broadway as a [[musical theatre|musical]] star in the 1990s, winning a [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Tony Award]] for his performance in ''[[How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying]]''. Broderick then starred alongside [[Nathan Lane]] in the [[Mel Brooks]] 2001 stage version of ''[[The Producers (musical)|The Producers]]'' which was a critical and financial success. He played Leopold \"Leo\" Bloom, an accountant who co-produces a musical designed to fail, but which turns out to be successful. Broderick was nominated for another [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Tony Award]] but lost to his fellow co-star Nathan Lane. The musical went on to win the most Tony Awards in history with 12 wins.<ref>https://www.tonyawards.com/en_US/history/facts/index.html</ref> Broderick and Lane reprised their roles in the 2005 film adaptation of [[The Producers (2005 film)|the same name]].\n\nBroderick was reunited with his co-star from ''[[The Lion King]]'' and ''[[The Producers (musical)|The Producers]]'', [[Nathan Lane]], in ''[[The Odd Couple (play)|The Odd Couple]]'', which opened on Broadway in October 2005. He appeared on Broadway as a college professor in ''[[The Philanthropist (play)|The Philanthropist]]'', running April 10 through June 28, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jones|first=Kenneth|date=February 20, 2009|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/126496.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120605044907/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/126496.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 5, 2012|title=Broadway's Philanthropist, Starring Broderick, Goes on Sale|work=[[Playbill]]}}</ref> He returned to the Broadway stage in Spring 2012, to star in the musical ''[[Nice Work If You Can Get It (musical)|Nice Work If You Can Get It]]'', directed and choreographed by [[Kathleen Marshall]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Jones|first=Kenneth|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/151904-Kathleen-Marshall-To-Make-Matthew-Broderick-Tap-Happy-in-Broadways-Nice-Work-Musical-in-2012|title=Kathleen Marshall To Make Matthew Broderick Tap-Happy in Broadway's 'Nice Work' Musical in 2012|work=[[Playbill]]|date=June 16, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021130452/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/151904-Kathleen-Marshall-To-Make-Matthew-Broderick-Tap-Happy-in-Broadways-Nice-Work-Musical-in-2012|archivedate=October 21, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe made his [[West End theatre|West End]] debut in ''The Starry Messenger'' in May 2019, co-starring with [[Elizabeth McGovern]].<ref>Meyer, Dan. [http://www.playbill.com/article/read-what-london-critics-thought-of-kenneth-lonergans-the-starry-messenger-starring-matthew-broderick-and-elizabeth-mcgovern# \"Read What London Critics Thought of Kenneth Lonergan\u2019s 'The Starry Messenger', Starring Matthew Broderick and Elizabeth McGovern\"] Playbill, May 30, 2019</ref>\n\nIn 2018, it was announced that Broderick was cast in the main role of Michael Burr in the [[Netflix]] [[comedy-drama]] series ''[[Daybreak (2019 TV series)|Daybreak]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/matthew-broderick-star-daybreak-netflix-series-the-conners-abc-recurring-jackie-love-interest-fxs-better-things-1202486201/|title=Matthew Broderick To Star In \u2018Daybreak\u2019 Netflix Series, Will Recur On ABC\u2019s \u2018The Conners\u2019 & FX\u2019s \u2018Better Things\u2019|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=October 19, 2018|access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Family===\n[[File:Matthew Broderick and Sarah Jessica Parker 2009.jpg|thumb|left|Broderick with wife [[Sarah Jessica Parker]] in 2009]]\nBroderick and actress [[Sarah Jessica Parker]] married on May 19, 1997, in Manhattan's [[Lower East Side]], in a ceremony officiated by his sister, Janet Broderick Kraft, an [[Episcopal Church in the USA|Episcopal]] [[priest]].<ref name=people1997>{{cite news|url=https://people.com/archive/love-stealth-vol-47-no-21/|title=Love & Stealth|author=Staff|date=June 2, 1997|accessdate=May 16, 2019|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|volume=47|issue=21| archivedate= May 21, 2017|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170521221930/https://people.com/archive/love-stealth-vol-47-no-21/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-04-05/episcopal-priest-janet-broderick-battles-coronavirus|title=Over Lent, this Beverly Hills priest battled coronavirus: 'I didn\u2019t know what plans Jesus had for me'|last=Goffard|first=Christopher|date=2020-04-05|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nParker and Broderick have a son, James, born October 28, 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://people.com/celebrity/parker-and-broderick-name-baby-james/|title=Parker and Broderick Name Baby James|first= Mark|last=Armstrong|work=People|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=May 16, 2019}}</ref><!--name and date announced by parents and their representative in People magazine cover story--> The couple had twin daughters Marion and Tabitha, born June 22, 2009, via surrogacy.<!--names, date, surrogacy as parents announced in statement to media--><ref>{{cite web|last=Fleeman|first=Mike|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20286959,00.html|title=Sarah Jessica Parker and Matthew Broderick Reveal Twins' Names|work=People|date=June 23, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"twins\">{{cite web|last=Mitovich|first=Matt|date=June 23, 2009|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Parker-Broderick-twins-1007199.aspx|title=Sarah Jessica Parker and Matthew Broderick Welcome Twin Girls|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the couple lives in the [[West Village]],<ref name=\"Observer\">{{cite news |last1=Halberg |first1=Morgan |title=Sarah Jessica Parker and Matthew Broderick Just Bought a $34.5M West Village Mega-Mansion |url=https://observer.com/2016/06/sarah-jessica-parker-and-matthew-broderick-just-bought-a-34-5m-west-village-megamansion/ |accessdate=February 13, 2019 |newspaper=Observer |date=June 8, 2016}}</ref> Broderick and Parker spend a large amount of time at their second home in [[Kilcar]], a village in [[County Donegal]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], where Broderick spent his summers as a child.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/sarah-jessica-parker-and-family-in-ireland-for-summer/|publisher=Evoke|title=Sarah Jessica Parker: Ireland 'Feels like home'|date=June 9, 2015|access-date=June 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525150707/http://evoke.ie/showbiz/sarah-jessica-parker-and-family-in-ireland-for-summer|archive-date=May 25, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> They also have a house in [[The Hamptons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hookedonhouses.net/2009/04/29/sarah-jessica-parker-matthew-brodericks-hamptons-house/|title=Sarah Jessica Parker & Matthew Broderick's Hamptons House|publisher=Hooked on Houses|date=June 18, 2009|accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBroderick is a [[Modern liberalism in the United States|political liberal]].<ref>http://redalertpolitics.com/2016/10/06/sarah-jessica-parker-trump-fans-may-shoot-us-hollywood-liberals/</ref>\n\n===Family ancestry===\nIn March 2010, Broderick was featured in the [[NBC]] program ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (U.S. TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]''. Broderick stated that his participation in the ancestry research program emotionally reconnected him with the role he played in ''Glory'' 22 years earlier, as he discovered a paternal great-great-grandfather, Robert Martindale, was a [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] soldier. A veteran of the [[Battle of Gettysburg]], Martindale, who belonged to the [[20th Connecticut Infantry Regiment|20th Connecticut]], was killed in the aftermath of the [[Battle of Atlanta]] and was eventually interred in an unnamed grave at the [[Marietta National Cemetery]]. Having identified the grave with the help of historian Brad Quinlin, Broderick's research enabled him to give his ancestor his name back. In the same program, Broderick discovered that his paternal grandfather, James Joseph Broderick II, whom he had never known, had been a highly decorated combat medic in [[World War I]], having earned his distinctions during the [[Meuse-Argonne Offensive]].<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\"/>\n\n===1987 car crash===\nOn August 5, 1987, while driving a rented [[BMW 3 Series (E30)|BMW 316]] in [[Enniskillen]], [[Northern Ireland]], Broderick crossed into the wrong lane and collided head-on with a [[Volvo]] driven by Anna Gallagher, 28,<ref>{{cite web |title=Broderick To Be Tried in Car Crash Death |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/08/arts/broderick-to-be-tried-in-car-crash-death.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=23 August 2019 |date=8 September 1987}}</ref> accompanied by her mother, Margaret Doherty, 63, killing both instantly. He was vacationing with [[Jennifer Grey]], whom he began dating in semi-secrecy during the filming of ''Ferris Bueller's Day Off''; the crash publicly revealed their relationship. He had a fractured leg and ribs, a concussion, and a collapsed lung. Grey received minor injuries, including whiplash.\n\nBroderick told police he had no recollection of the crash and did not know why he was in the wrong lane: \"I don't remember the day. I don't remember even getting up in the morning. I don't remember making my bed. What I first remember is waking up in the hospital, with a very strange feeling going on in my leg.\" He was charged with causing death by dangerous driving and faced up to five years in prison, but was later convicted of the lesser charge of careless driving and fined \u00a3100 (US$175).<ref>{{cite news |last=Monaghan |first=Gabrielle |date=September 26, 2010 |title=Fermanagh car crash \u2018ended Dirty Dancing star\u2019s career\u2019 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/fermanagh-car-crash-endeddirty-dancing-stars-career-jjf7tdc60j7 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=People87>{{cite web|last=Hutchings|first=David|date=September 14, 1987|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20097106,00.html|title=Jennifer Grey (Joel's Baby and Matthew Broderick's Lady) Turns Up the Heat in Dirty Dancing|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}</ref><ref name=NewYorkPost>{{cite web|first=Bill|last=Hoffmann |title=Broderick's Guilt|work=[[New York Post]]|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/broderick_guilt_actor_car_meet_with_AeAFxJ0tfIK0OzUmQteqYN|date=September 2, 2002|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Broderick To Be Tried in Car Crash Death|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/08/arts/broderick-to-be-tried-in-car-crash-death.html|date=September 8, 1987|accessdate=February 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Matthew Broderick Injured in Car Crash|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/08/07/arts/matthew-broderick-injured-in-car-crash.html|date=August 7, 1987|accessdate=February 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe victims' son and brother, Martin Doherty, called the verdict \"a travesty of justice\". He later forgave Broderick, amid plans to meet with him in 2003, to gain a sense of closure. In February 2012, when Broderick was featured in a multi-million-dollar [[Honda]] commercial aired during the [[Super Bowl]], Doherty said the meeting had not taken place and that Broderick \"wasn't the greatest choice of drivers, knowing his past.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.impartialreporter.com/news/roundup/articles/2012/02/09/395744-broderick-not-a-great-choice/ |title=Broderick not a great choice|first=Sarah|last=Saunderson|date=February 9, 2012|work=Impartial Reporter|publisher=William Trimble Ltd|location=Ireland|accessdate=May 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Max Dugan Returns]]''\n| Mi