broderick-mn0000337237|label=Matthew Broderick}}\n* [https://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2004/05/18/60II/main618124.shtml 2004 Story] from ''[[60 Minutes II]]''\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Matthew Broderick\n|list =\n{{TonyAward MusicalLeadActor 1976-2000}}\n{{TonyAward PlayFeaturedActor 1976-2000}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Broderick, Matthew}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American comedians]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Obie Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from Greenwich Village]]\n[[Category:Walden School (New York City) alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American film, stage and voice actor}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Matthew Broderick\n| image       = Matthew Broderick 2012.jpg\n| caption     = Broderick in 2012\n| birth_name  = Matthew John Broderick\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1962|3|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| occupation  = {{hlist|[[Actor]]|[[comedian]]|[[Singing|singer]]}}\n| years_active = 1981\u2013present\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Sarah Jessica Parker]]|May 19, 1997}}\n| children    = 3\n| father      = [[James Broderick]]\n| mother      = [[Patricia Broderick]]\n| relatives   = [[Milton H. Biow]] (grandfather)\n}}\n'''Matthew John Broderick''' (born March 21, 1962)<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Sim|first=David|title=MATTHEW BRODERICK'S BIRTHDAY: HIS 15 BEST MOVIES RANKED|date=21 March 2019|magazine=[[Newsweek]]|url=https://www.newsweek.com/matthew-broderick-birthday-best-movies-ranked-age-1369680|accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref> is an American actor, comedian and singer. His roles include the [[Golden Globe]]-nominated portrayal of the title character in ''[[Ferris Bueller's Day Off]]'' (1986), the voice of the adult [[Simba]] in [[Disney]]'s [[The Lion King (franchise)|''The Lion King'' trilogy]] (1994\u20132004), and [[Leo Bloom]] in both the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[The Producers (musical)|The Producers]]'' and its 2005 [[The Producers (2005 film)|film adaptation]]. Other films he had starring credits in include ''[[WarGames]]'' (1983), ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]'' (1989), ''[[The Freshman (1990 film)|The Freshman]]'' (1990), ''[[The Cable Guy]]'' (1996), ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]'' (1998), ''[[Election (1999 film)|Election]]'' (1999), ''[[Inspector Gadget (film)|Inspector Gadget]]'' (1999) and ''[[You Can Count on Me]]'' (2000).  Broderick also directed himself in ''[[Infinity (film)|Infinity]]'' (1996) and provided voice work in ''[[Good Boy!]]'' (2003), ''[[Bee Movie]]'' (2007), and ''[[The Tale of Despereaux (film)|The Tale of Despereaux]]'' (2008).\n\nBroderick has won two [[Tony Awards]], one for [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play|Best Featured Actor in a Play]] for ''[[Brighton Beach Memoirs]]'' (1983), and one for [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]] for ''[[How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying]]'' (1995).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/stars/matthew-broderick/profile/|title=Matthew Broderick Biography|work=Broadway.com|accessdate=March 14, 2014}}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, Broderick remains the youngest winner of the Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play.<ref>{{cite web|author= Nicholas Ephram Ryan Daniels|title=25 facts you probably didn't know about Matthew Broderick|date=15 July 2019|publisher=[[London Theatre Direct]]|url=https://www.londontheatredirect.com/news/25-facts-you-probably-didnt-know-about-matthew-broderick|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, for his contributions to the film industry, Matthew Broderick was inducted into the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] with a [[List of actors with Hollywood Walk of Fame motion picture stars|motion pictures star]] located at 6801 [[Hollywood Boulevard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/matthew-broderick |title=Hollywood Walk of Fame - Matthew Broderick |website=walkoffame.com |publisher=Hollywood Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=November 30, 2017}}</ref> Eleven years later, Broderick earned induction into the [[American Theater Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/audra-mcdonald-matthew-broderick-marin-mazzie-among-2017-theater-hall-of-fame-inductees|title=Audra McDonald, Matthew Broderick, Marin Mazzie among 2017 Theater Hall of Fame Inductees|publisher=www.playbill.com|accessdate=December 29, 2017}}</ref> Broderick starred as Michael Burr in the [[Netflix]] comedy series ''[[Daybreak (2019 TV series)|Daybreak]]'' (2019).\n\n==Early life and education==\nBroderick was born in [[Manhattan]], New York, the son of [[Patricia Broderick|Patricia]] ([[Married and maiden names|n\u00e9e]] Biow), a playwright, actress, and painter, and [[James Broderick]], an actor<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography: Patricia Broderick|url=http://www.tibordenagy.com/artists/broderick.html|publisher=Tibor de Nagy|year=2008|accessdate=May 19, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061216130646/http://www.tibordenagy.com/artists/broderick.html|archivedate=December 16, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and a [[World War II]] veteran.<ref name=huffingtonpost.com>{{cite web|last=Smolenyak|first=Megan|title=Matthew Broderick, Who Do You Think You Are?|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/megan-smolenyak-smolenyak/matthew-broderick-who-do-_b_825260.html|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=February 18, 2011}}</ref> His mother was [[Jewish]], a descendant of Jewish immigrants from Germany and Poland.<ref name=tca>Stated on ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]'', 2005</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Tugend|title=Bialystock and Bloom Tell the Truth|url=http://jewishjournal.com/culture/arts/12403/|work=JewishJournal|date=December 16, 2005|accessdate=May 19, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Nate|last=Bloom|url=http://www.stljewishlight.com/features/article_27d2ff80-db75-11e7-81ca-3346fc71e048.html|title='Tis the season for the Goldbergs to face the 'December Dilemma'|work=[[St. Louis Jewish Light]]|date=December 7, 2017|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Austin|last=O'Connor|url=https://www.aarp.org/entertainment/television/info-2017/matthew-broderick-interview-fd.html|title=Matthew Broderick's Christmas Presence|work=[[AARP]]|date=December 14, 2017|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Barbara|last=Hoffman|url=https://nypost.com/2018/04/19/matthew-broderick-cynthia-nixon-will-have-to-work-for-my-vote/|title=Matthew Broderick: Cynthia Nixon will have to work for my vote|work=[[New York Post]]|date=April 19, 2018|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=1429337|title=Excerpt: 'Stars of David : Prominent Jews Talk About Being Jewish' by Abigail Pogrebin|work=[[ABC News]]|date=December 26, 2005|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref> His father was a Catholic of Irish, and some English, descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.progenealogists.com/matthew-broderick-who-do-you-think-you-are.htm |title=Matthew Broderick: 'Who Do You Think You Are?'|first=Kyle J.|last=Betit|publisher=ProGenealogists|date=April 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413062601/http://www.progenealogists.com/matthew-broderick-who-do-you-think-you-are.htm|archivedate=April 13, 2010|url-status=live|accessdate=May 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Celia|last=McGee|title=Broderick's Set to Bloom in 'Producers'|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|date=April 18, 2001|url=http://www.matthewbroderick.net/article/nydaily01.html|via=Shinanat Mahamaytakit|accessdate=December 13, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116143804/http://matthewbroderick.net/article/nydaily01.html|archivedate=November 16, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Seal|first=Mark|title=Magical Mystery Tour|url=http://www.matthewbroderick.net/interview/americanway060101.html|work=American Way|date=January 1, 2006|via=Shinanat Mahamaytakit|accessdate=May 19, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517080611/http://www.matthewbroderick.net/interview/americanway060101.html|archivedate=May 17, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Broderick attended grade school at [[City and Country School]] in Manhattan and high school at the private [[Walden School (New York City)|Walden School]], also in [[Manhattan]].<ref name=fymb>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZmgaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RioEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2913%2C4478449|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]. Milwaukee Journal|title=For young Matthew Broderick, stage and movies are his campus|last=Kornbluth|first=Jesse|date=April 7, 1985|page=1, Entertainment}}</ref> He received acting training at [[HB Studio]].<ref>[https://hbstudio.org/about-hb-studio/alumni/ HB Studio Almuni]</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Matthew Broderick.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Broderick in Sweden during his promotion of ''[[Ferris Bueller's Day Off]]'']]\nBroderick's first major acting role came in an [[HB Studio]] workshop production of playwright [[Horton Foote]]'s ''On Valentine's Day'', playing opposite his father, who was a friend of Foote's. This was followed by a supporting role as [[Harvey Fierstein]]'s gay adopted son, David, in the [[Off-Broadway]] production of Fierstein's ''[[Torch Song Trilogy]]''; then, a good review by ''[[The New York Times]]'' theater critic [[Mel Gussow]] brought him to the attention of [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. Broderick commented on the effects of that review in a 2004 ''[[60 Minutes II]]'' interview:\n\n<blockquote>Before I knew it, I was like this guy in a hot play. And suddenly, all these doors opened. And it's only because Mel Gussow happened to come by right before it closed and happened to like it. It's just amazing. All these things have to line up that are out of your control.</blockquote>\n\nHe followed that with the role of Eugene Morris Jerome in the [[Neil Simon]] ''[[Eugene Trilogy]]'' including the plays ''[[Brighton Beach Memoirs]]'' and ''[[Biloxi Blues]]''. He won the [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play]] for his role in ''Brighton Beach Memoirs''.\n\nHis first film role was also written by Neil Simon. Broderick debuted in ''[[Max Dugan Returns]]'' (1983). His first big hit film was ''[[WarGames]]'', a summer hit in [[1983 in film|1983]],<ref name=tstbhl>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=eeIhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=JGMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6966%2C1801595|work=[[Pittsburgh Press]]|last=Siskel|first=Gene|title=Matthew Broderick toast of Broadway, Hollywood|date=July 19, 1983|page=A7}}</ref> in which he played the main role of David Lightman, a [[Seattle]] teen [[Hacker (term)|hacker]]. This was followed by the role of Philippe Gaston in ''[[Ladyhawke (film)|Ladyhawke]]'', in 1985.<ref name=fymb/><ref name=strstsc>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kkwyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cuUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6868%2C4657278|work=Lawrence Journal-World|location=Kansas|last=Thomas|first=Bob|title=Matthew Broderick has string of stage, screen successes|date=June 22, 1986|page=3D}}</ref>\n\nBroderick then won the role of the charming, clever slacker in the [[1986 in film|1986]] film ''[[Ferris Bueller's Day Off]]''. At the age of 23, Broderick played a high school student who, with his girlfriend and best friend, [[truant|plays hooky]] and explores [[Chicago]]. The film is a 1980s comedy favorite, and is one of Broderick's best known roles (particularly with teenage audiences).  Also in 1987, he played Air Force research assistant Jimmy Garrett in ''[[Project X (1987 film)|Project X]]''. In 1988, Broderick played [[Harvey Fierstein]]'s gay lover, Alan, in the screen adaptation of ''[[Torch Song Trilogy]]''.\n\nHe starred in the 1989 film ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]'' alongside [[Cary Elwes]], [[Morgan Freeman]], and [[Denzel Washington]], where he received favorable reviews for his portrayal of the [[American Civil War]] officer [[Robert Gould Shaw]], whom Broderick incidentally physically resembled at the time.\n\nIn the 1990s, Broderick was the voice of the adult [[Simba]], in Disney's successful animated film ''[[The Lion King]]'', and also voiced Tack the Cobbler in [[Miramax]]'s controversial version of ''[[The Thief and the Cobbler]]'', which had originally been intended as a silent role. He won recognition for two [[black comedy|dark comedy]] roles. The first was that of a bachelor in ''[[The Cable Guy]]'' with [[Jim Carrey]]. The second was that of a high school teacher in Alexander Payne's ''[[Election (1999 film)|Election]]'' with [[Reese Witherspoon]].\n\nBroderick returned to Broadway as a [[musical theatre|musical]] star in the 1990s, winning a [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Tony Award]] for his performance in ''[[How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying]]''. Broderick then starred alongside [[Nathan Lane]] in the [[Mel Brooks]] 2001 stage version of ''[[The Producers (musical)|The Producers]]'' which was a critical and financial success. He played Leopold \"Leo\" Bloom, an accountant who co-produces a musical designed to fail, but which turns out to be successful. Broderick was nominated for another [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Tony Award]] but lost to his fellow co-star Nathan Lane. The musical went on to win the most Tony Awards in history with 12 wins.<ref>https://www.tonyawards.com/en_US/history/facts/index.html</ref> Broderick and Lane reprised their roles in the 2005 film adaptation of [[The Producers (2005 film)|the same name]].\n\nBroderick was reunited with his co-star from ''[[The Lion King]]'' and ''[[The Producers (musical)|The Producers]]'', [[Nathan Lane]], in ''[[The Odd Couple (play)|The Odd Couple]]'', which opened on Broadway in October 2005. He appeared on Broadway as a college professor in ''[[The Philanthropist (play)|The Philanthropist]]'', running April 10 through June 28, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jones|first=Kenneth|date=February 20, 2009|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/126496.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120605044907/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/126496.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 5, 2012|title=Broadway's Philanthropist, Starring Broderick, Goes on Sale|work=[[Playbill]]}}</ref> He returned to the Broadway stage in Spring 2012, to star in the musical ''[[Nice Work If You Can Get It (musical)|Nice Work If You Can Get It]]'', directed and choreographed by [[Kathleen Marshall]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Jones|first=Kenneth|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/151904-Kathleen-Marshall-To-Make-Matthew-Broderick-Tap-Happy-in-Broadways-Nice-Work-Musical-in-2012|title=Kathleen Marshall To Make Matthew Broderick Tap-Happy in Broadway's 'Nice Work' Musical in 2012|work=[[Playbill]]|date=June 16, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021130452/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/151904-Kathleen-Marshall-To-Make-Matthew-Broderick-Tap-Happy-in-Broadways-Nice-Work-Musical-in-2012|archivedate=October 21, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe made his [[West End theatre|West End]] debut in ''The Starry Messenger'' in May 2019, co-starring with [[Elizabeth McGovern]].<ref>Meyer, Dan. [http://www.playbill.com/article/read-what-london-critics-thought-of-kenneth-lonergans-the-starry-messenger-starring-matthew-broderick-and-elizabeth-mcgovern# \"Read What London Critics Thought of Kenneth Lonergan\u2019s 'The Starry Messenger', Starring Matthew Broderick and Elizabeth McGovern\"] Playbill, May 30, 2019</ref>\n\nIn 2018, it was announced that Broderick was cast in the main role of Michael Burr in the [[Netflix]] [[comedy-drama]] series ''[[Daybreak (2019 TV series)|Daybreak]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/matthew-broderick-star-daybreak-netflix-series-the-conners-abc-recurring-jackie-love-interest-fxs-better-things-1202486201/|title=Matthew Broderick To Star In \u2018Daybreak\u2019 Netflix Series, Will Recur On ABC\u2019s \u2018The Conners\u2019 & FX\u2019s \u2018Better Things\u2019|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=October 19, 2018|access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Family===\n[[File:Matthew Broderick and Sarah Jessica Parker 2009.jpg|thumb|left|Broderick with wife [[Sarah Jessica Parker]] in 2009]]\nBroderick and actress [[Sarah Jessica Parker]] married on May 19, 1997, in Manhattan's [[Lower East Side]], in a ceremony officiated by his sister, Janet Broderick Kraft, an [[Episcopal Church in the USA|Episcopal]] [[priest]].<ref name=people1997>{{cite news|url=https://people.com/archive/love-stealth-vol-47-no-21/|title=Love & Stealth|author=Staff|date=June 2, 1997|accessdate=May 16, 2019|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|volume=47|issue=21| archivedate= May 21, 2017|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170521221930/https://people.com/archive/love-stealth-vol-47-no-21/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-04-05/episcopal-priest-janet-broderick-battles-coronavirus|title=Over Lent, this Beverly Hills priest battled coronavirus: 'I didn\u2019t know what plans Jesus had for me'|last=Goffard|first=Christopher|date=2020-04-05|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nParker and Broderick have a son, James, born October 28, 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://people.com/celebrity/parker-and-broderick-name-baby-james/|title=Parker and Broderick Name Baby James|first= Mark|last=Armstrong|work=People|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=May 16, 2019}}</ref><!--name and date announced by parents and their representative in People magazine cover story--> The couple had twin daughters Marion and Tabitha, born June 22, 2009, via surrogacy.<!--names, date, surrogacy as parents announced in statement to media--><ref>{{cite web|last=Fleeman|first=Mike|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20286959,00.html|title=Sarah Jessica Parker and Matthew Broderick Reveal Twins' Names|work=People|date=June 23, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"twins\">{{cite web|last=Mitovich|first=Matt|date=June 23, 2009|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Parker-Broderick-twins-1007199.aspx|title=Sarah Jessica Parker and Matthew Broderick Welcome Twin Girls|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=June 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the couple lives in the [[West Village]],<ref name=\"Observer\">{{cite news |last1=Halberg |first1=Morgan |title=Sarah Jessica Parker and Matthew Broderick Just Bought a $34.5M West Village Mega-Mansion |url=https://observer.com/2016/06/sarah-jessica-parker-and-matthew-broderick-just-bought-a-34-5m-west-village-megamansion/ |accessdate=February 13, 2019 |newspaper=Observer |date=June 8, 2016}}</ref> Broderick and Parker spend a large amount of time at their second home in [[Kilcar]], a village in [[County Donegal]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], where Broderick spent his summers as a child.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/sarah-jessica-parker-and-family-in-ireland-for-summer/|publisher=Evoke|title=Sarah Jessica Parker: Ireland 'Feels like home'|date=June 9, 2015|access-date=June 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525150707/http://evoke.ie/showbiz/sarah-jessica-parker-and-family-in-ireland-for-summer|archive-date=May 25, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> They also have a house in [[The Hamptons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hookedonhouses.net/2009/04/29/sarah-jessica-parker-matthew-brodericks-hamptons-house/|title=Sarah Jessica Parker & Matthew Broderick's Hamptons House|publisher=Hooked on Houses|date=June 18, 2009|accessdate=May 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBroderick is a [[Modern liberalism in the United States|political liberal]].<ref>http://redalertpolitics.com/2016/10/06/sarah-jessica-parker-trump-fans-may-shoot-us-hollywood-liberals/</ref>\n\n===Family ancestry===\nIn March 2010, Broderick was featured in the [[NBC]] program ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (U.S. TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]''. Broderick stated that his participation in the ancestry research program emotionally reconnected him with the role he played in ''Glory'' 22 years earlier, as he discovered a paternal great-great-grandfather, Robert Martindale, was a [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] soldier. A veteran of the [[Battle of Gettysburg]], Martindale, who belonged to the [[20th Connecticut Infantry Regiment|20th Connecticut]], was killed in the aftermath of the [[Battle of Atlanta]] and was eventually interred in an unnamed grave at the [[Marietta National Cemetery]]. Having identified the grave with the help of historian Brad Quinlin, Broderick's research enabled him to give his ancestor his name back. In the same program, Broderick discovered that his paternal grandfather, James Joseph Broderick II, whom he had never known, had been a highly decorated combat medic in [[World War I]], having earned his distinctions during the [[Meuse-Argonne Offensive]].<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\"/>\n\n===1987 car crash===\nOn August 5, 1987, while driving a rented [[BMW 3 Series (E30)|BMW 316]] in [[Enniskillen]], [[Northern Ireland]], Broderick crossed into the wrong lane and collided head-on with a [[Volvo]] driven by Anna Gallagher, 28,<ref>{{cite web |title=Broderick To Be Tried in Car Crash Death |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/08/arts/broderick-to-be-tried-in-car-crash-death.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=23 August 2019 |date=8 September 1987}}</ref> accompanied by her mother, Margaret Doherty, 63, killing both instantly. He was vacationing with [[Jennifer Grey]], whom he began dating in semi-secrecy during the filming of ''Ferris Bueller's Day Off''; the crash publicly revealed their relationship. He had a fractured leg and ribs, a concussion, and a collapsed lung. Grey received minor injuries, including whiplash.\n\nBroderick told police he had no recollection of the crash and did not know why he was in the wrong lane: \"I don't remember the day. I don't remember even getting up in the morning. I don't remember making my bed. What I first remember is waking up in the hospital, with a very strange feeling going on in my leg.\" He was charged with causing death by dangerous driving and faced up to five years in prison, but was later convicted of the lesser charge of careless driving and fined \u00a3100 (US$175).<ref>{{cite news |last=Monaghan |first=Gabrielle |date=September 26, 2010 |title=Fermanagh car crash \u2018ended Dirty Dancing star\u2019s career\u2019 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/fermanagh-car-crash-endeddirty-dancing-stars-career-jjf7tdc60j7 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=People87>{{cite web|last=Hutchings|first=David|date=September 14, 1987|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20097106,00.html|title=Jennifer Grey (Joel's Baby and Matthew Broderick's Lady) Turns Up the Heat in Dirty Dancing|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}</ref><ref name=NewYorkPost>{{cite web|first=Bill|last=Hoffmann |title=Broderick's Guilt|work=[[New York Post]]|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/broderick_guilt_actor_car_meet_with_AeAFxJ0tfIK0OzUmQteqYN|date=September 2, 2002|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Broderick To Be Tried in Car Crash Death|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/08/arts/broderick-to-be-tried-in-car-crash-death.html|date=September 8, 1987|accessdate=February 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Matthew Broderick Injured in Car Crash|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/08/07/arts/matthew-broderick-injured-in-car-crash.html|date=August 7, 1987|accessdate=February 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe victims' son and brother, Martin Doherty, called the verdict \"a travesty of justice\". He later forgave Broderick, amid plans to meet with him in 2003, to gain a sense of closure. In February 2012, when Broderick was featured in a multi-million-dollar [[Honda]] commercial aired during the [[Super Bowl]], Doherty said the meeting had not taken place and that Broderick \"wasn't the greatest choice of drivers, knowing his past.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.impartialreporter.com/news/roundup/articles/2012/02/09/395744-broderick-not-a-great-choice/ |title=Broderick not a great choice|first=Sarah|last=Saunderson|date=February 9, 2012|work=Impartial Reporter|publisher=William Trimble Ltd|location=Ireland|accessdate=May 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Max Dugan Returns]]''\n| Michael McPhee\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[WarGames]]''\n| David Lightman\n| \n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[1918 (1985 film)|1918]]''\n| Brother Vaughn\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Ladyhawke (film)|Ladyhawke]]''\n| Philippe Gaston\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Ferris Bueller's Day Off]]''\n| Ferris Bueller\n| \n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[On Valentine's Day]]''\n| Brother Vaughn\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Project X (1987 film)|Project X]]''\n| Jimmy Garrett\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Biloxi Blues (film)|Biloxi Blues]]''\n| Eugene Morris Jerome\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Torch Song Trilogy (film)|Torch Song Trilogy]]''\n| Alan Simon\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Family Business (1989 film)|Family Business]]''\n| Adam McMullen\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]''\n| Col. [[Robert Gould Shaw]]\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[The 